DeWine declares state of emergency|date=9 March 2020|access-date=9 March 2020}}</ref> Ohio restaurants and bars shuttered March 15, by 9 p.m., less than six hours before closures set to take place. first state.<ref>{{cite web|author=Randy Ludlow |url=https://www.dispatch.com/news/20200315/coronavirus-governor-orders-ohio-bars-restaurants-to-shut-down |title=Coronavirus: Governor orders Ohio bars, restaurants to shut down |work=The Columbus Dispatch |date=Mar 23, 2020 |accessdate=2020-04-05}}</ref> On March 18, DeWine ordered nail and hair salons, barbershops, and tattoo parlors closed. He also closed all but five [[Ohio Bureau of Motor Vehicles|Bureau of Motor Vehicles]] offices.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news5cleveland.com/news/continuing-coverage/coronavirus/gov-dewine-orders-closure-of-all-barbershops-nail-salons-tattoo-parlors-and-all-but-5-ohio-bmvs|title=Gov. DeWine orders closure of all barbershops, nail salons, tattoo parlors, and all but 5 Ohio BMVs|date=March 18, 2020|website=WEWS|accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref> On March 20, record-level rains led to flash flooding in Central Ohio.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rodriguez |first=Eddy |url=https://www.newsweek.com/flash-flooding-sweeps-through-columbus-central-ohio-1493507 |title=Flash Flooding Sweeps Through Central Ohio |work=Newsweek |date=2020-03-20 |accessdate=2020-04-05}}</ref> 61 people from Franklin and Licking County were placed in hotels due to house flood damage. The Red Cross stated it would normally open a shelter, but wouldn't due to the coronavirus threat.<ref>{{cite web|author=Mark Ferenchik |url=https://www.dispatch.com/news/20200323/flood-damage-assessed-from-torrential-rains-in-central-ohio |title=Flood damage assessed from torrential rains in central Ohio |work=The Columbus Dispatch |date= |accessdate=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://myfox28columbus.com/news/local/flooding-adds-insult-to-injury-for-central-ohioans-dealing-with-coronavirus |title=Flooding adds insult to injury for Central Ohioans dealing with coronavirus &#124; WTTE |publisher=Myfox28columbus.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\n===Timeline===\n[[File:Columbus coronavirus protests at the Ohio Statehouse, 2020-04-25.jpg|thumb|Protesting the shutdown and business closures at the [[Ohio Statehouse]], April 18, 2020]]\n[[File:Columbus, OH - COVID 02.jpg|thumb|upright|One of many business closure signs in [[the Short North]]]]\nEvents:<ref name=\"CUrefs\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.columbusunderground.com/coronavirus-covid-19-updates-in-columbus-sp1|title=Coronavirus / COVID-19 Updates in Columbus|date=March 24, 2020|accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.columbus.gov/coronavirus/|title=Coronavirus Outbreak 2019|website=www.columbus.gov|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dispatch.com/news/20200404/columbus-area-parks-officials-monitoring-use-as-ohio-closes-hocking-hills-state-park-over-coronavirus|title=Columbus area parks officials monitoring use as Ohio closes Hocking Hills State Park over coronavirus|last=Narciso|first=Dean|website=The Columbus Dispatch|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://columbusregion.com/covid-19-preparing-for-the-future/|title=COVID-19: Preparing for the Future|website=One Columbus|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\n* March 2: Columbus Public Health, the city's health department, issues tips for coronavirus\n* March 10: Ohio reports first cases, state of emergency declared in Ohio\n* March 12: first cases of community spread in Ohio; DeWine orders limiting gatherings to fewer than 100 individuals\n* March 13: the Columbus Board of Health declares a local public health emergency\n* March 14: Columbus reports its first case of coronavirus\n* March 16: DeWine limits gatherings to no more than 50 people; most county municipal court hearings are postponed; visitors prohibited from jails and correctional facilities\n* March 17: second case of coronavirus reported in Columbus, suggesting community spread\n* March 18: Mayor Ginther declares a local state of emergency; Columbus alters parking rules; Department of Building and Zoning Services closes its public office and cancels upcoming meetings; Area Commissions cancels two months of meetings\n* March 20: first coronavirus-related death in Ohio; street sweeping delayed in Columbus\n* March 22: DeWine gives a [[stay-at-home order]] for Ohio\n* March 23: first coronavirus-related deaths in Franklin County\n*March 24: DeWine outlines what is considered \"essential businesses and industries\" during the \"[[Stay-at-home order|Stay at home]]\" order he conducted\n*March 25: all Federal Tax filling and payment deadlines have all been pushed to July 15\n*March 31: New homeless shelters have been opened for men, woman and families who have been diagnosed with COVID-19 or is showing symptoms of the virus\n*April 2: DeWine has extended the stay at home order through May 1\n*April 3: The Columbus-area [[Hocking Hills State Park]] has been closed due to COVID-19<ref name=\":0\" />\n*April 5: 416 confirmed cases of COVID-19 reported in Columbus and [[Worthington, Ohio|Worthington]]\n*April 9: During a coronavirus briefing at the [[Ohio Statehouse]], about 50 people protested Governor DeWine and [[Amy Acton]], director of the [[Ohio Department of Health]], in opposition to the stay-at-home order.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abc6onyourside.com/news/local/protesters-gather-outside-of-statehouse-saying-they-want-to-go-back-to-work|title=Protesters gather outside of statehouse saying they want to go back to work|first=Jessi|last=Starkey|date=April 9, 2020|website=WSYX}}</ref>\n*April 13: Protests were held again outside the Statehouse, with signs reading \"Stop the tyranny,\" \"Survival is not living,\" and \"Quarantine worse than virus\", among statements against DeWine and Acton.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fox8.com/news/coronavirus/protesters-back-at-ohio-statehouse-during-coronavirus-news-conference/|title=Protesters back at Ohio Statehouse during coronavirus news conference|date=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Cases==\n{{expand section|date=April 2020}}\nThe first case of an infected Columbus resident was reported on March 14. The resident tested positive after returning from a cruise.<ref name=\"Ferenchik\">{{cite web|author=Mark Ferenchik |url=https://www.dispatch.com/news/20200314/columbus-man-among-26-ohioans-diagnosed-with-coronavirus |title=Columbus man among 26 Ohioans diagnosed with coronavirus |work=The Columbus Dispatch |date= |accessdate=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nAs of April 5, 2020, there are currently 4,043 cases and 119 total deaths in the entire state of Ohio, however in Columbia, Ohio there 416 cases confirmed in Columbus and Worthington.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==Government response==\n{{Main|U.S. state and local government response to the 2020 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{expand section|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Economic impact==\n{{Main|Socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{See also|Financial impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n[[File:Engine House No. 16 (Columbus, Ohio).jpg|thumb|Empty downtown street, March 22]]\n[[File:Easton Town Center closed.jpg|thumb|[[Easton Town Center]], a major mall complex, in March]]\nDue to the COVID-19 outbreak schools were closed on March 17 and will remain close until May 1. All of Ohio's state playgrounds, cabins, marinas, golf courses and campgrounds have been closed. \n\nGovernor [[Mike DeWine]] issued a stay at home order for all Ohio's citizens until May 1 with the exception of citizens who provides essential services and has closed all non-essential indoors business like arcades and laser tag. \n\nThe COVID-19 outbreak has caused record-breaking levels of unemployment which has caused 187,784 citizens to file for unemployment and by the end of the week ending in March 27 was followed by 272,117.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Business closures and event cancellations===\n{{Main|List of events affected by the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{expand section|date=April 2020}}\n\n====Film industry and the performing arts====\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on cinema}}\n{{expand section|date=April 2020}}\n\n====Food service and restaurant industry====\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the restaurant industry}}\n{{See also|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the restaurant industry in the United States}}\n{{expand section|date=April 2020}}\nThe city's restaurant industry was impacted by the state's bar and restaurant ban.\n\n====Hospitality industry====\nThe [[hospitality industry]] also experienced a wave of guest cancellations followed by a decline in bookings.\n\n====Impact on professional sports====\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports}}\n{{expand section|date=April 2020}}\n<!--[[Arnold Classic]]-->\n\n==Impact on education==\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on education}}Due to [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]], Ohio State University and other colleges and universities in the city cancelled in-person classes, moving to remote learning for the remainder of the semester. Additionally, with Governor [[Mike DeWine]] ordering all K-12 schools across the state to close through May 1, Columbus City Schools moved to remote learning during the closure. Columbus City Schools, along with other area school districts, began meal programs to provide to students under the age of 18.<ref name=\"CUrefs\" />\n\n==Impact on public transport==\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on public transport}}\n[[File:COTA rollsign 01.jpg|thumb|upright=1.1|[[Central Ohio Transit Authority|COTA]] buses notify riders to board using rear doors only]]\n\nIn early March, as the pandemic began affecting Ohio, the city's public transit ridership began dropping, approximately 40 percent. Its public transit agency [[Central Ohio Transit Authority|COTA]] began by introducing thorough cleaning measures, followed by reducing several rush hour services on March 17. On March 19, it suspended fare collection, making all rides temporarily free, and required passengers to board and depart buses from the rear doors. On the same day, it also modified all rush hour lines, and suspended its AirConnect and Night Owl services. On March 20, the agency recommended only using its services for essential travel; two days later it shut down several rush hour services and reduced frequencies of nine crosstown lines. On March 24, it stopped all rush hour services until further notice.<ref name=\"COVID\">{{Cite web |title=Major Service Change Announcements|work=Central Ohio Transit Authority|accessdate=March 19, 2020|url=https://www.cota.com/major-service-change-announcements/}}</ref> On March 26, the agency began \"dynamic service\" to pick up customers left at bus stops by too-full buses; the agency's current policy is for a maximum of 20 passengers per bus.<ref name=\"transit\">{{cite web|title=For Essential Travel, COTA and CoGo Are Still Available (But Scooters Aren't)|work=Columbus Underground|date=March 26, 2020|accessdate=March 28, 2020|url=https://www.columbusunderground.com/for-essential-workers-cota-and-cogo-are-still-available-but-scooters-arent-bw1}}</ref> On March 28, a COTA bus operator tested positive for the disease.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abc6onyourside.com/news/local/cota-employee-tests-postive-for-coronavirus |title=COTA employee tests postive for coronavirus &#124; WSYX |publisher=Abc6onyourside.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> On March 30, COTA suspended service on routes 21, 25, and 35.<ref name=\"COVID\"/> On April 7, a second driver tested positive for the disease.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abc6onyourside.com/news/local/second-cota-bus-driver-tests-positive-for-covid-19-drivers-concerned|title=Second COTA bus driver tests positive for COVID-19, drivers concerned|first=Mary|last=Smith|date=April 7, 2020|website=WSYX}}</ref> On the 11th, the agency announced it will require passengers to wear face masks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abc6onyourside.com/news/local/cota-to-require-customers-to-wear-masks|title=COTA to require customers to wear masks on all transit vehicles|first=Sarah Wynn, Mary|last=Smith|date=April 11, 2020|website=WSYX}}</ref>\n\n==Impact on religion==\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on religion}}\n{{expand section|date=April 2020}}\n\n== Closures ==\n[[File:COSI sign.jpg|thumb|upright|[[COSI (museum)|COSI]]'s entrance way sign, March 2020]]\n* On March 13, [[Columbus Recreation and Parks]] closed all locations through April 3, followed by [[Columbus Metropolitan Library]] and [[Columbus Zoo and Aquarium]] closing all of their locations through April 6.<ref name=\"CUrefs\" />\n* [[Columbus Museum of Art]], [[Franklin Park Conservatory]], [[COSI]] (Center of Science and Industry), and [[National Veterans Memorial and Museum]] also shut there doors with  COSI closing through April 3 and the [[National Veterans Memorial and Museum]] closing through April 8.<ref name=\"CUrefs\" />\n* On March 16, All gyms, fitness centers, movie theaters, bowling alleys, public recreation centers, indoor water parks and trampoline parks followed by Hollywood Casino are closed.<ref name=\"CUrefs\" />\n* On March 18, BMV closes a majority of its locations (180 locations) but still operating 5 of its locations. Salons, spas, barbershops, nail salons, and tattoo parlors are closed as well.<ref name=\"CUrefs\" />\n* On March 20, Columbus Idea Foundry lays of all of its workers with the inclusion of Columbus Idea Foundry CEO Casey McCarty.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://themetropreneur.com/columbus/columbus-idea-foundry-lays-off-staff/|title=Columbus Idea Foundry Lays Off Staff - The Metropreneur|last=Evans|first=Walker|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref name=\"CUrefs\" />\n* On March 25, Gateway Film Center Lays off a majority of workers due to COVID-19.\n* On March 31, Columbus Recreation and Parks/Columbus Metropolitan Library both extend their closure of all locations through May 1 for (Columbus Recreation and Parks) and May 2 for (Columbus Metropolitan Library).<ref name=\"CUrefs\" />\n* On April 1, the [[YMCA]] also lays of a majority of its workers.<ref name=\"CUrefs\" />\n* On April 3, Hocking State Park became the first Ohio state park to close due to COVID-19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dispatch.com/news/20200404/columbus-area-parks-officials-monitoring-use-as-ohio-closes-hocking-hills-state-park-over-coronavirus|title=Columbus area parks officials monitoring use as Ohio closes Hocking Hills State Park over coronavirus|last=Narciso|first=Dean|website=The Columbus Dispatch|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livescience.com/ohio-coronavirus-updates.html|title=Ohio: Latest updates on coronavirus|last=April 2020|first=Stephanie Pappas-Live Science Contributor 04|website=livescience.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n<!--By date?\n[[Columbus Metropolitan Library]] system\n[[Columbus Museum of Art]]\nGovernment, parks, schools, major businesses\nCameron Mitchell https://www.dispatch.com/business/20200319/coronavirus-cameron-mitchell-closes-all-restaurants-creates-relief-fund-for-4500-laid-off-workers-->\n\n=References=\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|COVID-19 pandemic in Columbus, Ohio}}\n* {{official website|https://www.columbus.gov/coronavirus/}}\n* [https://radio.wosu.org/post/coronavirus-ohio-march-24-april-10#stream/0 March 24 to April 10 updates]\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Ohio|Pandemic|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Ohio|Columbus]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by city|Columbus]]\n[[Category:21st century in Columbus, Ohio|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Ohio]]\n[[Category:Health in Ohio]]\n[[Category:February 2020 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States|Coronavirus outbreak]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "name_user": "\u2c6e", "label": "safe", "comment": "(GR)File renamed:File:Columbus coronavirus protests at the Ohio Statehouse, 2020-04-25.jpg\u2192File:Columbus coronavirus protests at the Ohio Statehouse, 2020-04-18c.jpgwrong date from auto numbering", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Columbus,_Ohio"}
{"title_page": "Solar eclipse of March 31, 2071", "text_new": "{{Infobox solar eclipse|2071Mar31}}\n\nAn annular [[solar eclipse]] will occur on March 31, 2071. A solar eclipse occurs when the [[Moon]] passes between [[Earth]] and the [[Sun]], thereby totally or partly obscuring the image of the Sun for a viewer on Earth. An annular solar eclipse occurs when the Moon's [[apparent diameter]] is smaller than the Sun's, blocking most of the Sun's light and causing the Sun to look like an [[Annulus (mathematics)|annulus]] (ring). An annular eclipse appears as a partial eclipse over a region of the Earth thousands of kilometres wide.\n\n== Related eclipses ==\n\n=== Solar eclipses 2069\u20132072===\n{{Solar eclipse set 2069\u20132072}}\n\n=== Saros 140 ===\n\nIt is a part of [[Solar Saros 140|Saros cycle 140]], repeating every 18 years, 11 days, containing 71 events. The series started with partial solar eclipse on April 16, 1512. It contains total eclipses from July 21, 1656 through November 9, 1836, hybrid eclipses from November 20, 1854 through December 23, 1908, and annular eclipses from January 3, 1927 through December 7, 2485. The series ends at member 71 as a partial eclipse on June 1, 2774. The longest duration of totality was 4 minutes, 10 seconds on August 12, 1692.\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\"\n!colspan=3|Series members 23\u201333 occur between 1901 and 2100:\n|-\n!23\n!24\n!25\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|[[File:SE1908Dec23H.png|150px]]<br />[[solar eclipse of December 23, 1908|Dec 23, 1908]]\n|[[File:SE1927Jan03A.png|150px]]<br />[[solar eclipse of January 3, 1927|Jan 3, 1927]]\n|[[File:SE1945Jan14A.png|150px]]<br />[[solar eclipse of January 14, 1945|Jan 14, 1945]]\n|- \n!26\n!27\n!28\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|[[File:SE1963Jan25A.png|150px]]<br />[[solar eclipse of January 25, 1963|Jan 25, 1963]]\n|[[File:SE1981Feb04A.png|150px]]<br />[[solar eclipse of February 4, 1981|Feb 4, 1981]]\n|[[File:SE1999Feb16A.png|150px]]<br />[[solar eclipse of February 16, 1999|Feb 16, 1999]]\n|- \n!29\n!30\n!31\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|[[File:SE2017Feb26A.png|150px]]<br />[[solar eclipse of February 26, 2017|Feb 26, 2017]]\n|[[File:SE2035Mar09A.png|150px]]<br />[[solar eclipse of March 9, 2035|Mar 9, 2035]]\n|[[File:SE2053Mar20A.png|150px]]<br />[[solar eclipse of March 20, 2053|Mar 20, 2053]]\n|- \n!32\n!33\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|[[File:SE2071Mar31A.png|150px]]<br />[[solar eclipse of March 31, 2071|Mar 31, 2071]]\n|[[File:SE2089Apr10A.png|150px]]<br />[[solar eclipse of April 10, 2089|Apr 10, 2089]]\n|}\n\n===Inex series===\n{{Inex eclipse set info}}\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\"\n!colspan=3| Inex series members between 1901 and 2100:\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|[[File:SE1926Jul09A.png|150px]]<br />[[solar eclipse of July 9, 1926|July 9, 1926]]<br />(Saros 135)\n|[[File:SE1955Jun20T.png|150px]]<br />[[solar eclipse of June 20, 1955|June 20, 1955]]<br />(Saros 136)\n|[[File:SE1984May30A.png|150px]]<br />[[solar eclipse of May 30, 1984|May 30, 1984]]<br />(Saros 137)\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|[[File:SE2013May10A.png|150px]]<br />[[solar eclipse of May 10, 2013|May 10, 2013]]<br />(Saros 138)\n|[[File:SE2042Apr20T.png|150px]]<br />[[solar eclipse of April 20, 2042|April 20, 2042]]<br />(Saros 139)\n|[[File:SE2071Mar31A.png|150px]]<br />[[solar eclipse of March 31, 2071|March 31, 2071]]<br />(Saros 140)\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|[[File:SE2100Mar10A.png|150px]]<br />[[solar eclipse of March 10, 2100|March 10, 2100]]<br />(Saros 141)\n|\n|}\n\n=== Metonic cycle ===\n{{Metonic eclipse set info}}\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\"\n!colspan=5|21 eclipse events between June 12, 2029 and June 12, 2105\n|-\n!June 11\u201312\n!March 30\u201331\n!January 16\n!November 4\u20135\n!August 23\u201324\n|-\n!118\n!120\n!122\n!124\n!126\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|[[File:SE2029Jun12P.png|150px]]<br />[[Solar eclipse of June 12, 2029|June 12, 2029]]\n|[[File:SE2033Mar30T.png|150px]]<br />[[Solar eclipse of March 30, 2033|March 30, 2033]]\n|[[File:SE2037Jan16P.png|150px]]<br />[[Solar eclipse of January 16, 2037|January 16, 2037]]\n|[[File:SE2040Nov04P.png|150px]]<br />[[Solar eclipse of November 4, 2040|November 4, 2040]]\n|[[File:SE2044Aug23T.png|150px]]<br />[[Solar eclipse of August 23, 2044|August 23, 2044]]\n|-\n!128\n!130\n!132\n!134\n!136\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|[[File:SE2048Jun11A.png|150px]]<br />[[Solar eclipse of June 11, 2048|June 11, 2048]]\n|[[File:SE2052Mar30T.png|150px]]<br />[[Solar eclipse of March 30, 2052|March 30, 2052]]\n|[[File:SE2056Jan16A.png|150px]]<br />[[Solar eclipse of January 16, 2056|January 16, 2056]]\n|[[File:SE2059Nov05A.png|150px]]<br />[[Solar eclipse of November 5, 2059|November 5, 2059]]\n|[[File:SE2063Aug24T.png|150px]]<br />[[Solar eclipse of August 24, 2063|August 24, 2063]]\n|-\n!138\n!140\n!142\n!144\n!146\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|[[File:SE2067Jun11A.png|150px]]<br />[[Solar eclipse of June 11, 2067|June 11, 2067]]\n|[[File:SE2071Mar31A.png|150px]]<br />[[Solar eclipse of March 31, 2071|March 31, 2071]]\n|[[File:SE2075Jan16T.png|150px]]<br />[[Solar eclipse of January 16, 2075|January 16, 2075]]\n|[[File:SE2078Nov04A.png|150px]]<br />[[Solar eclipse of November 4, 2078|November 4, 2078]]\n|[[File:SE2082Aug24T.png|150px]]<br />[[Solar eclipse of August 24, 2082|August 24, 2082]]\n|-\n!148\n!150\n!152\n!154\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|[[File:SE2086Jun11T.png|150px]]<br />[[Solar eclipse of June 11, 2086|June 11, 2086]]\n|[[File:SE2090Mar31P.png|150px]]<br />[[Solar eclipse of March 31, 2090|March 31, 2090]]\n|[[File:SE2094Jan16T.png|150px]]<br />[[Solar eclipse of January 16, 2094|January 16, 2094]]\n|[[File:SE2097Nov04A.png|150px]]<br />[[Solar eclipse of November 4, 2097|November 4, 2097]]\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Solar eclipse NASA reference|2051/SE2071Mar31A|20710331}}\n\n{{Solar eclipses}}\n\n[[Category:Annular solar eclipses|2071 3 31]]\n[[Category:2071 in science]]\n[[Category:21st-century solar eclipses|2071 3 31]]\n\n{{Solar-eclipse-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox solar eclipse|2071Mar31}}\n\nAn annular [[solar eclipse]] will occur on March 31, 2071. A [[solar eclipse]] occurs when the [[Moon]] passes between [[Earth]] and the [[Sun]], thereby totally or partly obscuring the image of the Sun for a viewer on Earth. An annular solar eclipse occurs when the Moon's [[apparent diameter]] is smaller than the Sun's, blocking most of the Sun's light and causing the Sun to look like an [[Annulus (mathematics)|annulus]] (ring). An annular eclipse appears as a partial eclipse over a region of the Earth thousands of kilometres wide.\n\n== Related eclipses ==\n\n=== Solar eclipses 2069\u20132072===\n{{Solar eclipse set 2069\u20132072}}\n\n=== Saros 140 ===\n\nIt is a part of [[Solar Saros 140|Saros cycle 140]], repeating every 18 years, 11 days, containing 71 events. The series started with partial solar eclipse on April 16, 1512. It contains total eclipses from July 21, 1656 through November 9, 1836, hybrid eclipses from November 20, 1854 through December 23, 1908, and annular eclipses from January 3, 1927 through December 7, 2485. The series ends at member 71 as a partial eclipse on June 1, 2774. The longest duration of totality was 4 minutes, 10 seconds on August 12, 1692.\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\"\n!colspan=3|Series members 23\u201333 occur between 1901 and 2100:\n|-\n!23\n!24\n!25\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|[[File:SE1908Dec23H.png|150px]]<br />[[solar eclipse of December 23, 1908|Dec 23, 1908]]\n|[[File:SE1927Jan03A.png|150px]]<br />[[solar eclipse of January 3, 1927|Jan 3, 1927]]\n|[[File:SE1945Jan14A.png|150px]]<br />[[solar eclipse of January 14, 1945|Jan 14, 1945]]\n|- \n!26\n!27\n!28\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|[[File:SE1963Jan25A.png|150px]]<br />[[solar eclipse of January 25, 1963|Jan 25, 1963]]\n|[[File:SE1981Feb04A.png|150px]]<br />[[solar eclipse of February 4, 1981|Feb 4, 1981]]\n|[[File:SE1999Feb16A.png|150px]]<br />[[solar eclipse of February 16, 1999|Feb 16, 1999]]\n|- \n!29\n!30\n!31\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|[[File:SE2017Feb26A.png|150px]]<br />[[solar eclipse of February 26, 2017|Feb 26, 2017]]\n|[[File:SE2035Mar09A.png|150px]]<br />[[solar eclipse of March 9, 2035|Mar 9, 2035]]\n|[[File:SE2053Mar20A.png|150px]]<br />[[solar eclipse of March 20, 2053|Mar 20, 2053]]\n|- \n!32\n!33\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|[[File:SE2071Mar31A.png|150px]]<br />[[solar eclipse of March 31, 2071|Mar 31, 2071]]\n|[[File:SE2089Apr10A.png|150px]]<br />[[solar eclipse of April 10, 2089|Apr 10, 2089]]\n|}\n\n===Inex series===\n{{Inex eclipse set info}}\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\"\n!colspan=3| Inex series members between 1901 and 2100:\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|[[File:SE1926Jul09A.png|150px]]<br />[[solar eclipse of July 9, 1926|July 9, 1926]]<br />(Saros 135)\n|[[File:SE1955Jun20T.png|150px]]<br />[[solar eclipse of June 20, 1955|June 20, 1955]]<br />(Saros 136)\n|[[File:SE1984May30A.png|150px]]<br />[[solar eclipse of May 30, 1984|May 30, 1984]]<br />(Saros 137)\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|[[File:SE2013May10A.png|150px]]<br />[[solar eclipse of May 10, 2013|May 10, 2013]]<br />(Saros 138)\n|[[File:SE2042Apr20T.png|150px]]<br />[[solar eclipse of April 20, 2042|April 20, 2042]]<br />(Saros 139)\n|[[File:SE2071Mar31A.png|150px]]<br />[[solar eclipse of March 31, 2071|March 31, 2071]]<br />(Saros 140)\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|[[File:SE2100Mar10A.png|150px]]<br />[[solar eclipse of March 10, 2100|March 10, 2100]]<br />(Saros 141)\n|\n|}\n\n=== Metonic cycle ===\n{{Metonic eclipse set info}}\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\"\n!colspan=5|21 eclipse events between June 12, 2029 and June 12, 2105\n|-\n!June 11\u201312\n!March 30\u201331\n!January 16\n!November 4\u20135\n!August 23\u201324\n|-\n!118\n!120\n!122\n!124\n!126\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|[[File:SE2029Jun12P.png|150px]]<br />[[Solar eclipse of June 12, 2029|June 12, 2029]]\n|[[File:SE2033Mar30T.png|150px]]<br />[[Solar eclipse of March 30, 2033|March 30, 2033]]\n|[[File:SE2037Jan16P.png|150px]]<br />[[Solar eclipse of January 16, 2037|January 16, 2037]]\n|[[File:SE2040Nov04P.png|150px]]<br />[[Solar eclipse of November 4, 2040|November 4, 2040]]\n|[[File:SE2044Aug23T.png|150px]]<br />[[Solar eclipse of August 23, 2044|August 23, 2044]]\n|-\n!128\n!130\n!132\n!134\n!136\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|[[File:SE2048Jun11A.png|150px]]<br />[[Solar eclipse of June 11, 2048|June 11, 2048]]\n|[[File:SE2052Mar30T.png|150px]]<br />[[Solar eclipse of March 30, 2052|March 30, 2052]]\n|[[File:SE2056Jan16A.png|150px]]<br />[[Solar eclipse of January 16, 2056|January 16, 2056]]\n|[[File:SE2059Nov05A.png|150px]]<br />[[Solar eclipse of November 5, 2059|November 5, 2059]]\n|[[File:SE2063Aug24T.png|150px]]<br />[[Solar eclipse of August 24, 2063|August 24, 2063]]\n|-\n!138\n!140\n!142\n!144\n!146\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|[[File:SE2067Jun11A.png|150px]]<br />[[Solar eclipse of June 11, 2067|June 11, 2067]]\n|[[File:SE2071Mar31A.png|150px]]<br />[[Solar eclipse of March 31, 2071|March 31, 2071]]\n|[[File:SE2075Jan16T.png|150px]]<br />[[Solar eclipse of January 16, 2075|January 16, 2075]]\n|[[File:SE2078Nov04A.png|150px]]<br />[[Solar eclipse of November 4, 2078|November 4, 2078]]\n|[[File:SE2082Aug24T.png|150px]]<br />[[Solar eclipse of August 24, 2082|August 24, 2082]]\n|-\n!148\n!150\n!152\n!154\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|[[File:SE2086Jun11T.png|150px]]<br />[[Solar eclipse of June 11, 2086|June 11, 2086]]\n|[[File:SE2090Mar31P.png|150px]]<br />[[Solar eclipse of March 31, 2090|March 31, 2090]]\n|[[File:SE2094Jan16T.png|150px]]<br />[[Solar eclipse of January 16, 2094|January 16, 2094]]\n|[[File:SE2097Nov04A.png|150px]]<br />[[Solar eclipse of November 4, 2097|November 4, 2097]]\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Solar eclipse NASA reference|2051/SE2071Mar31A|20710331}}\n\n{{Solar eclipses}}\n\n[[Category:Annular solar eclipses|2071 3 31]]\n[[Category:2071 in science]]\n[[Category:21st-century solar eclipses|2071 3 31]]\n\n{{Solar-eclipse-stub}}\n", "name_user": "ComplexRational", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:rm duplink", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solar_eclipse_of_March_31,_2071"}
{"title_page": "Canada and the Vietnam War", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{CanWars20thC}}\n\nThe [[Vietnam War]] had considerable effects on Canada, but Canada and Canadians also affected the war.\n\nThe [[Government of Canada|Canadian government]] did not officially participate in the war.  However, it contributed to peacekeeping forces in 1973 to help enforce the [[Paris Peace Accords]].<ref name=\"harvardcitizen\">{{cite web|url=http://harvardcitizen.com/2007/03/21/why-canada-must-go-to-iraq/ |title=Why Canada Must Go To Iraq |last=Park |first=Thomas |date=March 21, 2007 |publisher=The Citizen \u2013 Newspaper of the Harvard Kennedy School |accessdate=November 18, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080828054005/http://harvardcitizen.com/2007/03/21/why-canada-must-go-to-iraq/ |archivedate=August 28, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nPrivately, some Canadians contributed to the war effort.  Canadian corporations sold [[Materiel|war material]] to the Americans. In addition, at least 30,000 Canadians [[Military volunteer|volunteered]] to serve in the American armed forces during the war.  At least 134 Canadians died or were reported missing in Vietnam.<ref name=Corday>Corday, Chris (10 November 2015).  \"[http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/lost-to-history-the-canadians-who-fought-in-vietnam-1.3304440  Lost to History: The Canadians Who Fought in Vietnam]\".  CBC News British Columbia.  Retrieved 5 December 2017.</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, tens of thousands of American Vietnam War resisters emigrated to Canada to [[Draft evasion|avoid the draft]].  Largely middle class and educated, they had a significant impact on Canadian life.<ref name=Fulford />  After the war, tens of thousands of [[Vietnamese boat people]] were also admitted and became a unique part of Canadian life.<ref name=Valerie />\n\n== Beginnings ==\n\nDuring the [[First Indochina War]] between France and the Indo-Chinese nationalist and communist parties, Canada remained militarily uninvolved but provided modest diplomatic and economic support to the French.  Canada was, however, part of the [[International Control Commission]] (along with Poland and India) that oversaw the [[Geneva Conference (1954)|1954 Geneva Agreements]] that divided Vietnam, provided for French withdrawal and would have instituted elections for reunification by 1956.  Behind the scenes, Canadian diplomats tried to discourage both France and the United States from escalating the conflict in a part of the world Canadians had decided was not strategically vital.{{Citation needed|date=February 2007}}\n\nCanada laid out six prerequisites to joining a war effort or Asian alliance like [[Southeast Asia Treaty Organization|SEATO]]:\n# It had to involve cultural and trade ties in addition to a military alliance.\n# It had to demonstrably meet the will of the people in the countries involved.\n# Other free Asian states had to support it directly or in principle.\n# France had to refer the conflict to United Nations.\n# Any multilateral action must conform to the [[United Nations Charter|UN charter]].\n# Any action had to be divorced from all elements of [[colonialism]].{{Citation needed|date=February 2007}}\n\nThese criteria effectively guaranteed Canada would not participate in the Vietnam War.\n\n== Canadian involvement in the war ==\n[[File:Lorne RodenBush -- Canadian observer during the War in Vietnam.jpg|thumb |right |alt=Canadian military officer standing in uniform beside Canadian flag |Colonel Lorne RodenBush was Canada's representative to the [[International Control Commission]] in Vietnam from 1967\u2013 \n68.<ref>Bardua, Rob (April 9, 2008).  \"[http://www.nationalmuseum.af.mil/news/story.asp?id=123093763 Canadian Colonel to Speak About His Experiences in Hanoi During the Vietnam War] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141103082754/http://www.nationalmuseum.af.mil/news/story.asp?id=123093763 |date=November 3, 2014 }}\".  National Museum of the US Air Force website.  Retrieved December 11, 2012.</ref>]]\nAt the start of the Vietnam War, Canada was a member of the [[International Control Commission]] (ICC) overseeing the implementation of the Geneva Agreements, and thus attempted to maintain an air of neutrality.  However, the Canadian negotiators were strongly on the side of the Americans. One representative ([[J. Blair Seaborn]], younger brother of [[Robert Seaborn]]) was even involved in secretly exchanging messages between the U.S. and North Vietnam on behalf of the Americans, with the approval of the Canadian government. Canada also sent foreign aid to South Vietnam, which, while humanitarian, was directed by the Americans.<ref name=\"Vietnam War\">\"[http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/en/article/vietnam-war/ \"Vietnam War\"]. ''The Canadian Encyclopedia.''</ref>\nCanada tried to mediate between the warring countries, aiming for a conclusion that could allow the U.S. to leave the conflict honorably, but also reportedly publicly (if mildly) criticized American war methods.{{Citation needed|date=February 2007}} Text of a speech which Canadian Prime Minister Lester Pearson gave at Temple University in Philadelphia in 1965 has debunked this widespread rumor, with Pearson even stating \"The government and great majority of people of my country have supported wholeheartedly the US peacekeeping and peacemaking policies in Vietnam.\"<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=J3_FBQAAQBAJ&pg=PT86&lpg=PT86&dq=The+government+and+great+majority+of+people+of+my+country+have+supported+wholeheartedly+the+US+peacekeeping+and+peacemaking+policies+in+Vietnam+lester+pearson&source=bl&ots=8oBPP0fHOk&sig=ACfU3U1gHp2va1K5ZBZUJKVRizvOtTAVtA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjj04WoloXlAhVFmK0KHZITBHsQ6AEwAXoECAgQAQ#v=onepage&q=The%20government%20and%20great%20majority%20of%20people%20of%20my%20country%20have%20supported%20wholeheartedly%20the%20US%20peacekeeping%20and%20peacemaking%20policies%20in%20Vietnam%20lester%20pearson&f=false|title=The Globalization of NATO: Intervention, Security and Identity|first=Veronica M.|last=Kitchen|accessdate=5 October 2019}}</ref><ref>https://yvesengler.com/2016/03/15/why-does-mainstream-keep-repeating-lies-about-lester-pearson/</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=9g4Xd12rIGYC&pg=PT88&lpg=PT88&dq=Linda+McQuaig++contributed+to+ending+the+U.S.+war+effort+in+Vietnam.&source=bl&ots=isGKlO1Yei&sig=Ju_jcwsBsMODmOLHHfz4946wJ8s&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiC_5i2sMLLAhVHlYMKHX4eAbEQ6AEIGzAA#v=onepage&q=Linda%20McQuaig%20%20contributed%20to%20ending%20the%20U.S.%20war%20effort%20in%20Vietnam.&f=false|title=Holding the Bully's Coat: Canada and the U.S. Empire|first=Linda|last=McQuaig|accessdate=5 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, Canadian industry exported military supplies and raw materials useful in their manufacture, including ammunition, [[napalm]] and [[Agent Orange]],<ref name=\"supplying\">[http://archives.cbc.ca/IDC-1-71-1413-9128/conflict_war/vietnam/clip7 Supplying the war machine] \u2013 [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]] Archives</ref> to the United States, as trade between the two countries carried on unhindered.\n\n\"500 firms sold $2.5 billion of war materials (ammunition, napalm, aircraft engines and explosives) to the Pentagon. Another $10 billion in food, beverages, berets and boots for the troops was exported to the U.S., as well as nickel, copper, lead, oil, brass for shell casings, wiring, plate armour and military transport. In Canada unemployment fell to record low levels of 3.9%\".<ref name=\"Vietnam War\"/>\n\nAlthough these exports were sales by Canadian companies, not gifts from the Canadian government, they benefited the American war effort nonetheless. The first official response to the economic support being given to the United States military from the government was by [[Lester B. Pearson]] on March 10, 1967 that the export of goods to their southern ally was \"necessary and logical\" due to the extreme integration of both economies, and that an embargo would also be a notice of withdrawal from North American defense arrangements.<ref>\"Thakur, Ramesh C.(1984). Peacekeeping in Vietnam: Canada, India, Poland, and the International Commission. The University of Alberta Press. p.205. {{ISBN|0-88864-037-4}}.</ref>\n\nAs the war escalated, relations between Canada and the United States deteriorated.  On April 2, 1965, Pearson gave a speech at [[Temple University]] in the United States which, in the context of firm support for U.S. policy, called for a pause in the bombing of North Vietnam. In a perhaps apocryphal story, when a furious [[President of the United States|President]] [[Lyndon B. Johnson]] met with Pearson the next day, he grabbed the much smaller Canadian by his lapels and talked angrily with him for an hour. After this incident, the two men somehow found ways to resolve their differences over the war\u2014in fact, they both had further contacts, including later twice meeting in Canada.<ref>{{cite book|last=Martin|first=Lawrence|title=The Presidents and the Prime Ministers|url=https://archive.org/details/presidentsprimem0000mart|url-access=registration}}</ref>\n\n== Assistance to the U.S. war effort ==\n\n[[File:DHC-4 Caribou Vietnam.jpg|thumb |upright=1.2 |right |alt=Large airplane descending over tarpaulin-covered area |A [[de Havilland Canada DHC-4 Caribou]] transport plane on landing approach, Vietnam War, 1971.]]\nCanada's official diplomatic position in relation to the Vietnam War was that of a non-belligerent, which imposed a ban on the export of war-related items to the combat areas.{{Citation needed|date=November 2007}} Nonetheless, Canadian industry was also a major supplier of equipment and supplies to the American forces, not sending these directly to [[South Vietnam]] but to the United States. Sold goods included relatively benign items like boots, but also aircraft, munitions, napalm and commercial [[defoliant]]s, the use of which was fiercely opposed by anti-war protesters at the time. \nIn accordance with the 1956<ref>[http://www.ccc.ca/en/canadian-exporters/~/media/9513A3BD3C1448FE8970C22641DD337C.ashx?la=en Full text] (pdf)</ref> [[Defence Production Sharing Agreement]], Canadian industry sold $2.47 billion in materiel to the United States between 1965 and 1973.<ref name = \"supplying\"/> Many of the companies were owned by US parent firms, but all export sales over $100,000 US (and thus, the majority of contracts) were arranged through the [[Canadian Commercial Corporation]], a [[crown corporation]] which acted as an intermediary between the [[United States Department of Defense]] and Canadian industry.<ref name = \"supplying\"/> In some cases Canadian defence contractors were even sent to the theatre of war to carry out company work such as when [[de Havilland Canada]] sent mobile repair teams from the Downsview (Toronto) plant to carry out depot level repair on battle damaged [[de Havilland Canada DHC-4 Caribou|de Havilland Caribou]] aircraft that were owned and operated by the U.S. Army. Furthermore, the [[Department of National Defence (Canada)|Canadian]] and the [[United States Department of Defense|American Defence departments]] worked together to test chemical defoliants for use in Vietnam.<ref name = \"finkelconrad\">This collaboration was only revealed to the public in 1981. \"History of the Canadian Peoples, 1867\u2013Present,\" Alvin Finkel & Margaret Conrad, 1998</ref> Canada also allowed their [[NATO]] ally to use Canadian facilities and bases for training exercises and weapons testing as per existing treaties.\n\nBetween January 28, 1973 and July 31, 1973, Canada provided 240 peacekeeping troops to ''Operation Gallant'', the peace keeping operation associated with the [[International Commission of Control and Supervision]] (ICCS) Vietnam, along with [[Hungary]], Indonesia, and [[Poland]].<ref name=\"moise\">[http://www.clemson.edu/caah/history/facultypages/EdMoise/icc.html Vietnam War Bibliography: The International Commissions: ICC (ICSC) and ICCS] Edwin Moise.</ref>  Their role was to monitor the cease-fire in South Vietnam per the [[Paris Peace Accords]].<ref>[http://www.vac-acc.gc.ca/remembers/sub.cfm?source=collections/cmdp/mainmenu/group06/icmvn Control and Supervision Vietnam 1973 \u2013 ICCS], Veterans Affairs Canada, March 26, 2001</ref> After Canada's departure from the Commission, it was replaced by [[Iran]].\n\n== Canadians in the U.S. military ==\n\n[[File:WindsorCanadianDeadVietnamwar.jpg|thumb |upright=1.2 |right |alt=Large brown house behind Canadian and American flags |The [[Canadian Vietnam Veterans Memorial]] in Windsor, Ontario, commemorates Canadians who died fighting alongside American forces in Vietnam.]]\n\n[[File:Peter C Lemon.jpg|thumb|right|alt=Head shot of a confident-looking young man in an Army uniform.|Toronto-born [[Peter C. Lemon]] served with distinction in the U.S. Army in Vietnam.]]\n\nIn a counter-current to the movement of American draft evaders and deserters to Canada, about 30,000 Canadians volunteered to fight in southeast Asia.<ref name=\"cbcsecretwar\">{{cite news| title =Canada's Secret War: Vietnam| publisher =CBC| url =http://archives.cbc.ca/IDD-1-71-1413/conflict_war/vietnam/| accessdate =April 7, 2007 }}</ref> Among the volunteers were fifty [[Mohawk nation|Mohawks]] from the [[Kahnawake|Kahnawake reserve]] near Montreal.<ref name=\"mohawksinvietnam\">{{cite book| last =Morrison| first =Wilbur H.| title =The Elephant and the Tiger| publisher =Hellgate Press| year =2001| page =597| isbn = 1-55571-612-1 }}</ref> One hundred ten Canadians died in Vietnam, and seven remain listed as [[Missing in Action|missing in action]]. U.S. Army [[Sergeant]]   [[Peter C. Lemon]], an American [[immigrant]] from Canada, was awarded the U.S. [[Medal of Honor]] for his valour in the conflict. (This cross-border enlistment was not unprecedented:  Both the [[World War I|First]] and the [[Second World War]] saw thousands of Americans join the Canadian Armed Forces before the U.S officially declared war on Germany)<ref name=\"Malley-Morrison2009\">{{cite book|author=Kathleen Malley-Morrison|title=State Violence and the Right to Peace: Western Europe and North America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hV-y4BNWTt0C&pg=PA167|accessdate=June 12, 2011|date=October 30, 2009|publisher=[[ABC-CLIO]]|isbn=978-0-275-99651-2|pages=167\u2013}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Windsor, Ontario]], there is a privately funded monument to the Canadians killed in the Vietnam War.<ref name=\"ontmonument\">{{cite web| title =Canadian Vietnam Memorial \u2013 \"The North Wall\"| publisher =Edna Barney (self published)| url =http://barneykin.com/northwall/| accessdate =April 7, 2007 }}</ref> In [[Melocheville, Quebec]], there is a monument dating from October 1989 funded by the Association Qu\u00e9b\u00e9coise des V\u00e9t\u00e9rans du Vietnam.<ref name=\"qcmonument\">{{cite web| title =Canadian Vietnam Veterans Monument| publisher =Association Qu\u00e9b\u00e9coise des V\u00e9t\u00e9rans du Vietnam| url =http://www.canadianvietnamvetsquebec.com/#!our-history/c1050}}</ref>\n\n==American war resisters in Canada==\n{{Main|War resister}}\nAmerican [[draft evasion|draft evaders]] (often referred to by the disparaging term \"draft dodgers\") and military [[deserter]]s who sought refuge in Canada during the Vietnam War would ignite controversy among those seeking to immigrate to Canada, some of it provoked by the Canadian government's initial refusal to admit those who could not prove that they had been discharged from [American] military service. This changed in 1968.<ref name=\"knowles\">{{Cite journal|last1= Knowles|first1=Valerie|title=Forging Our Legacy: Canadian Citizenship and Immigration, 1900\u20131977|publisher=[[Public Works and Government Services Canada]], [[Citizenship and Immigration Canada]]|year=2000|isbn=0662289838}}</ref> On May 22, 1969, Ottawa announced that immigration officials would not and could not ask about immigration applicants' military status if they showed up at the border seeking permanent residence in Canada.<ref name=\"cool\"/> According to Valerie Knowles, draft evaders were usually college-educated sons of the middle class who could no longer defer induction into the [[Selective Service System]]. Deserters, on the other hand, were predominantly sons of the lower-income and working classes who had been inducted into the armed services directly from high school or who had volunteered, hoping to obtain a skill and broaden their limited horizons.<ref name=\"knowles\"/>\n\nStarting in 1965, Canada became a choice haven for American draft evaders and deserters. Because they were not formally classified as refugees but were admitted as immigrants, there is no official estimate of how many draft evaders and deserters were admitted to Canada during the Vietnam War. One informed estimate puts their number between 30,000 and 40,000.<ref name=\"knowles\"/> Whether or not this estimate is accurate, the fact remains that emigration from the United States was high as long as America was involved militarily in the war and maintained compulsory military service; in 1971 and 1972 Canada received more immigrants from the United States than from any other country.<ref name=\"knowles\"/>\n\n=== Draft evaders ===\n{{main|Draft evasion}}\n[[File:Draft dodgers being counseled 1967.jpg|thumb |upright=1.2 |right |alt=Five young people sitting and talking intently |[[Mark Satin]] (left) counseling American Vietnam War evaders at the Anti-Draft Programme office in Toronto, 1967.]]\nEstimates vary greatly as to how many Americans settled in Canada for the specific reason of dodging the draft or \"evading [[conscription]],\" as opposed to desertion, or other reasons.  Canadian immigration statistics show that 20,000 to 30,000 draft-eligible American men came to Canada as immigrants during the Vietnam era. The [[BBC]] stated that \"as many as 60,000 young American men dodged the draft.\"<ref>{{cite news |first= Jeff|last=Gray |title=US deserter's Canadian campaign |date= July 6, 2004|publisher=BBC|accessdate=January 19, 2009|quote= |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/3867481.stm}}</ref>  Estimates of the total number of American citizens who moved to Canada due to their opposition to the war range from 50,000 to 125,000<ref name=\"dogers\">[http://www.cbc.ca/canada/story/2004/09/08/draft_dogers040908.html draft dodgers memorial to be built in B.C.], CBC News, 09/08/2004</ref> This exodus was \"the largest politically motivated migration from the United States since the [[United Empire Loyalist]]s moved north to oppose the [[American Revolution]].\"<ref name = \"strawberry\">\"On Strawberry Hill\" by Chris Turner in [[The Walrus]], September 2007.</ref> Major communities of war resisters formed in Montreal, the [[Slocan Valley]], British Columbia, and on [[Baldwin Village|Baldwin Street]] in [[Toronto]], Ontario.{{Citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\nThey were at first assisted by the Student Union for Peace Action, a campus-based Canadian anti-war group with connections to [[Students for a Democratic Society (1960 organization)|Students for a Democratic Society]].<ref>Clausen, Oliver (May 21, 1967).  \"Boys Without a Country\".  ''The New York Times Magazine'', p.&nbsp;25.</ref><ref>Williams, Roger N. (1971).  ''The New Exiles: War Resisters in Canada''.  Liveright Publishers, pp.&nbsp;\n61\u201364. {{ISBN|978-0-87140-533-3}}.</ref>  Canadian immigration policy at the time made it easy for immigrants from all countries to obtain legal status in Canada.<ref>Schreiber, Jan (January 1968).  \"Canada's Haven for Draft Dodgers\".  ''The Progressive'', p.&nbsp;34.</ref>  By late 1967, draft evaders were being assisted primarily by several locally based anti-draft groups (over twenty of them), such as the Vancouver Committee to Aid American War Objectors<ref>Berton, Pierre (1997).  ''1967: The Last Good Year''.  Doubleday Canada, p.&nbsp;202. {{ISBN|978-0-385-25662-9}}.</ref><ref>Williams, Roger N. (1971), cited above, pp.&nbsp;56\u201358.</ref> and the Toronto Anti-Draft Programme.<ref>Cowan, Edward (February 11, 1968).  \"Expatriate Draft Evaders Prepare Manual on How to Immigrate to Canada\".  ''The New York Times'', p. 7.</ref><ref>Hagan, John (2001).  ''Northern Passage: American Vietnam War Resisters in Canada''.  Harvard University Press, pp.&nbsp;74\u201380. {{ISBN|978-0-674-00471-9}}.</ref>  As a counselor for the Programme, [[Mark Satin]] wrote the ''Manual for Draft-Age Immigrants to Canada'' in 1968.<ref>Jones, Joseph (spring\u2013summer 2002).  \"The House of Anansi's Singular Bestseller\".  ''[[Canadian Notes & Queries]]'', issue no 61, p.&nbsp;19.</ref><ref name=Roy>[[Roy MacSkimming|MacSkimming, Roy]] (26 August 2017).  \"[https://beta.theglobeandmail.com/arts/books-and-media/book-reviews/review-mark-satins-manual-for-draft-age-immigrants-to-canada-is-just-as-timely-as-ever/article36087618  Review: Mark Satin's Manual for Draft-Age Immigrants to Canada Is Just as Timely as Ever]\". ''The Globe and Mail'' (Toronto), p.&nbsp;R12. Online dated one day earlier.  Retrieved 6 December 2017.</ref>  It sold nearly 100,000 copies overall.<ref>Adams, James (October 20, 2007).  \"[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/the-big-guys-keep-being-surprised-by-us/article696023 'The Big Guys Keep Being Surprised By Us']\". ''The Globe and Mail'' (Toronto), p.&nbsp;R6.  Retrieved December 12, 2012.</ref><ref name=Fulford>[[Robert Fulford (journalist)|Fulford, Robert]] (6 September 2017).  \"[https://nationalpost.com/entertainment/books/how-vietnam-war-draft-dodgers-became-a-lively-and-memorable-part-of-canadian-history  How Vietnam War Draft Dodgers Became a Lively and Memorable Part of Canadian History]\".  ''[[National Post]]'' (Canada), national edition, p.&nbsp;B5.  Retrieved 6 December 2017.</ref>  In 1970, Canadian singer [[Gordon Lightfoot]] recorded his song \"Sit Down Young Stranger\" to express his views on Canada's acceptance of American draft evaders.{{Citation needed|reason=Not obvious from lyrics|date=December 2017}}\n\n[[File:Hendricks-leboeuf2.jpg|thumb|right|alt=Joyful-looking male couple holding a wedding bouquet|Quebec gay rights advocate [[Michael Hendricks and Ren\u00e9 Leboeuf|Michael Hendricks]] (right) is one American war resister who affected Canadian life.]]\n\nThe influx of these young men, who (as mentioned earlier) were often well educated<ref name=\"knowles\"/><ref name=\"star20090705\">{{cite news |first=Sue |last= Bailey|title=Iraq war resisters decry Tories' website editing |url= https://www.thestar.com/article/661072|work=The Toronto Star|date= July 5, 2009|accessdate=July 22, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"letthemstay\">{{cite web | title=Vietnam War Resisters, Then and Now | url=http://www.letthemstay.ca/english_index.htm | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141109133025/http://www.letthemstay.ca/english_index.htm | url-status=dead | archive-date=November 9, 2014 | accessdate=May 24, 2009 }}</ref> and politically leftist, affected Canada's academic and cultural institutions, and Canadian society at large.  These new arrivals tended to balance the \"[[brain drain]]\" that Canada had experienced.  While some draft evaders returned to the United States after a [[pardon]] was declared in 1977 during the administration of [[Jimmy Carter]], roughly half of them stayed in Canada.<ref>Hagan, John (2001), cited above, pp.&nbsp;167 and&nbsp;242.</ref>\n\nProminent draft evaders who stayed in Canada permanently, or for a significant amount of time, have included:\n* Mike Fisher \u2013 founding member of [[Heart (band)|Heart]], notable rock/pop band<ref>[http://jam.canoe.ca/Music/Pop_Encyclopedia/H/Heart.html JAM! Music] \u2013 Pop Encyclopedia</ref>\n* [[William Gibson]] \u2013 science fiction writer, winner of a [[Nebula Award]]\n* [[Jim Green (councilman)|Jim Green]] \u2013 Vancouver city councillor and mayoral candidate\n* [[Michael Hendricks and Ren\u00e9 Leboeuf|Michael Hendricks]] \u2013 gay rights advocate<ref name=\"letthemstay\"/>\n* [[Jeffry House]] \u2013 lawyer, clients include many activists\n* Bill King \u2013 musician and organizer of Toronto's [[Beaches Jazz Festival]]<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.inthesetimes.com/article/6949/sanctuary_denied/ |title=Sanctuary Denied |author= Roman Goergen|date= February 23, 2011|magazine=[[In These Times]] |accessdate=March 6, 2011}}</ref>\n* Michael Klein \u2013 activist physician, spouse of [[Bonnie Sherr Klein]], father of [[Naomi Klein]]<ref name=\"cool\"/><ref name=\"letthemstay\"/>\n* [[Keith Maillard]] \u2013 professor or creative writing, [[University of British Columbia]]\n* [[Eric Nagler]] \u2013 children's entertainer on [[The Elephant Show]]\n* Wayne Robinson \u2013 father of [[Svend Robinson]], former Member of Parliament\n* [[Jay Scott]] \u2013 film critic, ''[[The Globe and Mail]]''\n* [[Jesse Winchester]] \u2013 singer-songwriter\n* Michael Wolfson \u2013 assistant chief statistician at [[Statistics Canada]]<ref name=\"cool\">{{cite web |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/insight/article/850824--daring-to-object-iraq-war-resisters-though-often-veterans-themselves-have-been-met-with-a-cool-reception-much-different-from-the-draft-dodgers-of-the-1960s |title=Iraq war resisters meet cool reception in Canada |author=Nicholas Keung |date=August 20, 2010 |work=Toronto Star |accessdate=August 24, 2010}}</ref>\n* Harry Yates \u2013 human resources manager at the Ministry of the [[Attorney General of British Columbia]]\n\n=== Deserters ===\n{{Main|Desertion}}\n[[File:Mike Tulley Interview - October 6 2010.ogv|thumb|upright=1.2|right|Interview with Mike Tulley, an American Vietnam War deserter who emigrated to Canada.  (For interview, click on gray arrow at lower left of photo.)]]\nDistinct from draft resisters, there were also deserters from the American forces who also made their way to Canada. There was pressure from the United States and Canada to have them arrested, or at least stopped at the border.{{Citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\nThe deserters have not been pardoned and may still face ''pro forma'' arrest, as the case of Allen Abney demonstrated in March 2006.<ref name=\"thecurrent\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/thecurrent/2006/200603/20060314.html|title=CBC Radio {{!}} The Current {{!}} Whole Show Blow-by-Blow|last=Tremonti|first=Anna Maria|date=March 14, 2006|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]], Radio, The Current|accessdate=January 21, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071119190933/http://www.cbc.ca/thecurrent/2006/200603/20060314.html|archivedate=November 19, 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"Abney\">{{citenews|title=Deserter says he was treated well by U.S. military|url=http://www.cbc.ca/canada/story/2006/03/20/abney060320.html|date=March 20, 2006|accessdate=January 27, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090822210447/http://www.cbc.ca/canada/story/2006/03/20/abney060320.html|archivedate=August 22, 2009}}, CBC News</ref>  Another similar case was that of Richard Allen Shields:   He had deserted the U.S. Army in Alaska in 1972 after serving a year in Vietnam. Twenty-eight years later, on March 22, 2000, while he attempted to drive a lumber truck across the US-Canada border (in Metaline Falls, Washington) he was arrested by U.S. Customs agents and jailed at [[Fort Sill]].\nHe was discharged from the Army with an [[Other Than Honorable]] discharge in April 2000.{{Citation needed|date=December 2017}}\nOther noteworthy deserters from that era include the following:\n* [[Andy Barrie]]- former host of [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] Radio's ''[[Metro Morning]]'' in [[Toronto]]<ref name=\"cool\" /><ref name=\"letthemstay\"/> (He later received a General Discharge from the United States Army, became a [[Canadians|Canadian]] citizen, and is free to travel to the U.S.)\n* Dick Cotterill<ref name=\"letthemstay\"/>\n* Michael Shaffer: \"After six months in the Army, my application for CO status was denied and I was told that I would be going to Vietnam. I refused to draw my weapon and was ordered court-martialed. On Labour Day 1970 I was able to escape and cross into Canada ... During [[Presidency of Gerald Ford#Clemency for draft dodgers|President Ford's Clemency Program]] in 1975, I went to Fort Dix seeking the \"Undesirable Discharge\" offered to deserters who turned themselves in. The Army decided that I wasn't eligible and court-martial proceedings were resumed. With help from the ACLU, I was released and two years later a Federal Court ordered the Army to discharge me Honourably as a Conscientious Objector ... I remained in Vancouver\"<ref name=\"letthemstay\"/>\n* [[Jack Todd (journalist)|Jack Todd]] \u2013 award-winning sports columnist for the ''[[Montreal Gazette]]''\n* Mike Tulley - [[Edmonton, Alberta]] area sound engineer and social activist<ref>(January 8, 2006) \"[http://www.canada.com/edmontonjournal/news/cityplus/story.html?k=76378&id=54e519a1-5289-4b95-9ce4-931ee14b8153 Soundman quietly supports his causes] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151019122906/http://www.canada.com/edmontonjournal/news/cityplus/story.html?k=76378&id=54e519a1-5289-4b95-9ce4-931ee14b8153 |date=October 19, 2015 }}\", [[Edmonton Journal]], Retrieved December 12, 2012</ref>\n\n===Missing-text controversy===\n\nIn February 2009, text on how both draft evaders and resisters of the Vietnam War were ultimately allowed to stay in Canada suddenly vanished from the website of the [[Department of Citizenship and Immigration Canada|Department of Citizenship and Immigration]] [[Government of Canada|Canada]].\"<ref name=\"star20090705\"/><ref name=\"Bailey\">{{cite news |first=Sue |last=Bailey |title=Federal website changes undermine Iraq resisters: critics |url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/canadianpress/article/ALeqM5iGSn-j73WQhIktgHT2tLCndsL_5A |publisher= [[The Canadian Press]] |date= July 5, 2009|accessdate=July 17, 2009}}</ref>\n\nOriginally, the [[Government of Canada]] website had contained the following statements:\n\n<blockquote>... Starting in 1965, Canada became a choice haven for American draft resisters and deserters, ... Although some of these transplanted Americans returned home after the Vietnam War, most of them put down roots in Canada, making up the largest, best-educated group this country had ever received.<ref name=\"star20090705\"/></blockquote>\n\nThe above statement (now gone from the website) was part of an extensive online chapter on draft resisters and deserters from the Vietnam war, which was found in the larger online document,\"Forging Our Legacy: Canadian Citizenship and Immigration, 1900\u20131977\"<ref name=\"knowles\"/> It was originally posted on the [[Government of Canada]] website in the year 2000, when the [[Liberal Party of Canada]], led by [[Jean Chr\u00e9tien]], was in power and responsible for the content of that website. But in 2009, [[28th Canadian Ministry|the Ministry]] of [[Stephen Harper]] [took] \"a much dimmer view of [[Canada and Iraq War Resisters|dozens of U.S. soldiers who've come north after refusing to serve]] in [[2003 invasion of Iraq|the invasion of Iraq]]. Some had already been [[Canada and Iraq War Resisters#Punishments given to Iraq War resisters|deported to face military jail terms ranging from about six to 15 months]].\"<ref name=\"star20090705\"/>\n\nThe removal from the [[Citizenship and Immigration Canada|Citizenship and Immigration]] website occurred in the same month that its multi-party counterpart, the  [[Standing committee (Canada)|Standing Committee]] on [[Citizenship and Immigration Canada|Citizenship and Immigration]] was debating that issue:  On February 12, 2009, that multi-party committee passed, for the second time, a [[non-binding motion]] reaffirming Parliament's earlier (June 2008) vote which recommended that the government let [[Canada and Iraq War Resisters|Iraq War resisters]] stay in Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.parl.gc.ca/HousePublications/Publication.aspx?DocId=3676589&Language=E&Mode=1&Parl=40&Ses=2 |title=Minutes of the meeting of The Standing Committee on Citizenship and Immigration, February 12, 2009 |publisher=.parl.gc.ca |accessdate=February 26, 2011}}</ref> A month and a half later, on March 30, 2009, the [[House of Commons of Canada]] again voted in a non-binding [[Motion (parliamentary procedure)|motion]] 129 to 125 in favour of the committee's recommendation.<ref>{{cite news |first= Alex|last= Cooper|title= Federal court to hear American war resister's appeal|url= https://www.thestar.com/article/622278|work=Toronto Star |date= April 21, 2009|accessdate=April 23, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.parl.gc.ca/HousePublications/Publication.aspx?Language=E&Mode=1&Parl=40&Ses=2&DocId=3781662#OOB-2683958 |title=40th PARLIAMENT, 2nd SESSION, EDITED HANSARD \u2022 NUMBER 036, CONTENTS, Monday, March 30, 2009 |publisher=.parl.gc.ca |accessdate=February 26, 2011}}</ref>\n\n== After the war ==\n\n[[File:35 Vietnamese boat people 2.JPEG|thumb|right|alt=Refugees crowded together on a boat|After the war, Canada admitted many [[Vietnamese boat people]] as immigrants.]]\n\nThe Vietnam War continued to resonate in Canada long after the war was over.\n\n=== Vietnamese boat people ===\n{{main|Vietnamese Canadians}}\n\nAfter the [[Fall of Saigon|fall of South Vietnam]] in April 1975, hundreds of thousands of refugees, called [[Vietnamese boat people|boat people]], fled Vietnam and adjacent nations.  According to Canadian immigration historian Valerie Knowles, from 1979 to 1980 Canada admitted an estimated 60,000 of these refugees, \"most of whom had endured several days in small, leaky boats, prey to vicious pirate attacks, before ending up in squalid camps\".<ref name=Valerie>Knowles, Valerie (2016).   ''Strangers at Our Gates: Canadian Immigration and Immigration Policy, 1540-2015''.  Toronto: Dundurn Press, 4th ed., p.&nbsp;216 (\"Boat People\" section).  {{ISBN|978-1-4597-3285-8}}.</ref>  Knowles says it was the highest number of boat people accepted by any nation, including the United States, during that period.<ref name=Valerie />  The boat people constituted 25% of all newcomers admitted to Canada from 1978 to 1981.<ref name=Valerie />  This created a substantial Vietnamese community in Canada, concentrated especially in [[Montreal]], [[Vancouver]], and [[Toronto]].{{Citation needed|date=May 2007}}\n\n=== Cultural and political shifts ===\n\nThe Vietnam War was an important cultural turning point in Canada.  Coupled with [[Canadian Centennial|Canada's centenary]] in 1967 and the success of [[Expo 67]], Canada became far more independent and nationalistic.  The public, if not their representatives in parliament, became more willing to oppose the United States and to move in a different direction socially and politically.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Young|first1=Joe|title=U.S. Aggression in Vietnam & Canada's Complicity |date=1969|publisher=Canada Vietnam Newsletter|location=Toronto |pages=11\u201313 |url=http://collections.mun.ca/PDFs/radical/USAggressioninVietnamandCanadasComplicity.pdf|accessdate=October 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Agent Orange in New Brunswick ===\n\nIn 1981, a government report revealed that [[Agent Orange]], the controversial defoliant, had been tested at [[CFB Gagetown]], New Brunswick.<ref name=\"CBC-Orange\">[http://archives.cbc.ca/IDC-1-71-1413-9130/conflict_war/vietnam/clip9 CBC Archives]\u2014A 1981 news broadcast on Vietnam era \"Agent Orange\" testing in Base Gagetown, New Brunswick</ref><ref name=\"cbcagentorangepurple\">[http://www.cbc.ca/news/background/agentorange/ Agent Orange and Agent Purple]. CBC. Published 2007-08-21. Retrieved December 19, 2011.</ref>  In June 1966, the chemical was sprayed over nearly <span style=\"white-space:nowrap\">600&nbsp;acres&nbsp;(2.4&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>)</span> of forest inside the base.  There are differing opinions about the level of toxicity of the site;<ref name=\"cbcagentorangecancerrates\">[http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/story/2007/08/21/nb-agentorangereport.html No evidence to link cancer rates to Agent Orange: report]. CBC. Published 2007-08-21. Retrieved December 19, 2011.</ref> but, in 2006, the Canadian government said it planned to compensate some of those who were exposed.  As of 2011, some claims have been paid but the administration of the compensation program has been criticized.<ref name=\"dndexfoliants\">[http://www.forces.gc.ca/site/reports-rapports/defoliant/index-eng.asp The Use of Herbicides at CFB Gagetown from 1952 to Present Day] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111212011559/http://www.forces.gc.ca/site/reports-rapports/defoliant/index-eng.asp |date=December 12, 2011 }}. Department of National Defence. Retrieved December 19, 2011.</ref><ref name=\"agentorangecomp\">[http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/story/2011/12/16/bc-agentorange.html Dying woman denied Agent Orange payout]. CBC. Retrieved December 19, 2011.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Canada|War}}\n*[[Opposition to United States involvement in the Vietnam War]]\n*[[Baldwin Village]] \u2013 a neighbourhood and commercial street in Toronto that became the centre of the American exile community\n*[[Canada and Iraq War resisters]]\n*[[Canada\u2013Vietnam relations]]\n*[[Military history of Australia during the Vietnam War]]\n*[[New Zealand in the Vietnam War]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*''Building Sanctuary: The Movement to Support Vietnam War Resisters in Canada, 1965\u20131973'', by Jessica Squires.  Vancouver: University of British Columbia Press, 2013.  {{ISBN|978-0-7748-2524-5}}.\n*''[https://web.archive.org/web/20120626135503/http://www.cic.gc.ca/english/resources/publications/legacy/index.asp Forging Our Legacy: Canadian Citizenship and Immigration, 1900\u20131977]'', by Valerie Knowles.  Ottawa: Public Works and Government Services Canada, 2000. {{ISBN|978-0-662-28983-8}}.\n*''I Volunteered: Canadian Vietnam Vets Remember'', by Tracey Arial.  Winnipeg: Watson & Dwyer Publishing, 1998. {{ISBN|978-1-896239-14-9}}.\n*''In the Interests of Peace: Canada and Vietnam, 1954\u20131973'', by Douglas A. Ross. Toronto: University of Toronto Press, 1984. {{ISBN|978-0-8020-5632-0}}.\n*''Manual for Draft-Age Immigrants to Canada'', by Mark Satin.  Toronto: House of Anansi Press, \"A List\" reprint edition, 2017, orig. 1968.  New introduction by Canadian historian [[James Laxer]], new afterword by Satin (\"Bringing Draft Dodgers to Canada in the 1960s\"). {{ISBN|978-1-4870-0289-3}}.\n*''The New Exiles: American War Resisters in Canada'', by Roger Neville Williams.  New York: Liveright Publishers, 1970.  Includes transcripts of interviews with resisters.  {{ISBN|978-0-87140-533-3}}.\n*''[https://books.google.com/books?id=s0cBZvIftU0C&lpg=PP1&dq=Northern%20Passage%3A%20American%20Vietnam%20War%20Resisters%20in%20Canada&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q&f=true Northern Passage: American Vietnam War Resisters in Canada]'', by John Hagan. Cambridge: Harvard University Press, 2001. {{ISBN|978-0-674-00471-9}}.\n*''Quiet Complicity: Canadian Involvement in the Vietnam War'', by Victor Levant.  Foreword by Gwynne Dyer.  Toronto: Between the Lines Books, 1987. {{ISBN|978-0-919946-72-9}}.\n*''Snow Job: Canada, the United States, and Vietnam (1954\u20131973)'', by Charles Taylor. Toronto: House of Anansi Press, 1974. {{ISBN|978-0-88784-619-9}}.\n*''Strangers at Our Gates: Canadian Immigration and Immigration Policy, 1540-2015'', by Valerie Knowles.  Toronto: Dundurn Press, 4th ed., 2016, p.&nbsp;214 (\"Draft-Age Americans in Canada\" section).  Incorporates and updates parts of the Knowles booklet cited in this article.  {{ISBN|978-1-4597-3285-8}}.\n*''Unknown Warriors: Canadians in the Vietnam War'', by Fred Gaffen.  Toronto: Dundurn Press, 1990. {{ISBN|978-1-55002-073-1}}.\n*\"[https://web.archive.org/web/20070930043731/http://thecanadianencyclopedia.com/index.cfm?PgNm=TCE&Params=A1ARTA0008367 Vietnam War]\", by Victor Levant.  On the ''Canadian Encyclopedia'' website.  Accessed 14 December 2012.\n*''War Is Here: The Vietnam War and Canadian Literature'', by Robert McGill.   Kingston, Canada: McGill-Queen's University Press, 2017.  {{ISBN|978-0-7735-5159-6}}.\n\n==External links==\n\n===The war===\n\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110426043344/http://cvvq-aqvv.typepad.com/ Association Qu\u00e9b\u00e9coise des V\u00e9t\u00e9rans du Vietnam]\n*[http://www.cbc.ca/archives/topic/canadas-secret-war-vietnam  Canada's Secret War: Vietnam].  Digital archives, [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]].  \n*[http://www.cvva.ca  Canadian Vietnam Veterans Association]\n*[http://www.canadiansinvietnam.com  Canadian Vietnam Veterans Memorial Association]\n*[http://www.glanmore.org/cdncas/memorialair.html North Wall, Canadian Vietnam Veterans Memorial]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20160912133447/http://www.vvic.org/ Vietnam Veterans in Canada].   Advocacy group.\n*[http://www.vwam.com/vets/allies/canadians.html Vietnam Veterans With a Mission].  Information and pictures.\n*[http://edmoise.sites.clemson.edu/internat.html#canada  Vietnam War Bibliography: Canada].  Compiled by scholar Edwin L. Morse.\n*[https://www.cbc.ca/radio/rewind/the-vietnam-war-canada-s-role-part-one-1.3038110  The Vietnam War: Canada's Role, Part One].  Transcript of a [[CBC Radio]] broadcast.\n\n===War immigrants===\n\n* [https://discoverarchives.library.utoronto.ca/index.php/jack-pocock-memorial-collection Jack Pocock Memorial Collection], in the [https://onesearch.library.utoronto.ca/discover-archives Discover Archives] at the University of Toronto.  Material from the Toronto Anti-Draft Programme and similar organizations, mostly from 1969\u20131975.\n*[http://www.radicalmiddle.com/manual.htm Manual for Draft-Age Immigrants to Canada].  Narrative and excerpt.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130731092403/http://fisher.library.utoronto.ca/sites/default/files/satin629.pdf Mark Satin Papers], in the [https://onesearch.library.utoronto.ca/discover-archives Discover Archives] at the University of Toronto.  Includes material from the Toronto Anti-Draft Programme, mostly from 1967\u20131968.\n*[http://www.cbc.ca/archives/topic/seeking-sanctuary-draft-dodgers Seeking Sanctuary: Draft Dodgers].  Digital archives, [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]].\n*[http://www.radicalmiddle.com/tadp.htm Toronto Anti-Draft Programme].  Self-description from 1968.\n*[http://www.cbc.ca/radio/rewind/the-vietnam-war-canada-s-role-part-two-the-boat-people-1.3048026  The Vietnam War: Canada's Role, Part Two: The Boat People].  Transcript of a [[CBC Radio]] broadcast.\n*[http://www.library.ubc.ca/jones/amcan.html Vietnam War Resisters in Canada], hosted by [[Vancouver Community Network]].  Annotated guide to texts and websites from the 1960s to the present. Compiled by scholar Joseph Jones.\n* [https://www150.statcan.gc.ca/n1/pub/89-621-x/89-621-x2006002-eng.htm  Vietnamese Community in Canada].  Overview by [[Statistics Canada]].\n\n{{Foreign relations of Canada|Vietnam War}}\n{{Canadian military history}}\n\n[[Category:Canada\u2013United States relations]]\n[[Category:Vietnam War]]\n[[Category:Opposition to United States involvement in the Vietnam War]]\n[[Category:Draft evasion]]\n[[Category:History of Canada (1960\u20131981)]]\n[[Category:Political history of Canada]]\n[[Category:Canada\u2013Vietnam relations]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{CanWars20thC}}\n\nThe [[Vietnam War]] had considerable effects on Canada, but Canada and Canadians also affected the war.\n\nThe [[Government of Canada|Canadian government]] did not officially participate in the war.  However, it contributed to peacekeeping forces in 1973 to help enforce the [[Paris Peace Accords]].<ref name=\"harvardcitizen\">{{cite web|url=http://harvardcitizen.com/2007/03/21/why-canada-must-go-to-iraq/ |title=Why Canada Must Go To Iraq |last=Park |first=Thomas |date=March 21, 2007 |publisher=The Citizen \u2013 Newspaper of the Harvard Kennedy School |accessdate=November 18, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080828054005/http://harvardcitizen.com/2007/03/21/why-canada-must-go-to-iraq/ |archivedate=August 28, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nPrivately, some Canadians contributed to the war effort.  Canadian corporations sold [[Materiel|war materiel]] to the Americans. In addition, at least 30,000 Canadians [[Military volunteer|volunteered]] to serve in the American armed forces during the war.  At least 134 Canadians died or were reported missing in Vietnam.<ref name=Corday>Corday, Chris (10 November 2015).  \"[http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/lost-to-history-the-canadians-who-fought-in-vietnam-1.3304440  Lost to History: The Canadians Who Fought in Vietnam]\".  CBC News British Columbia.  Retrieved 5 December 2017.</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, tens of thousands of American Vietnam War resisters emigrated to Canada to [[Draft evasion|avoid the draft]].  Largely middle class and educated, they had a significant impact on Canadian life.<ref name=Fulford />  After the war, tens of thousands of [[Vietnamese boat people]] were also admitted and became a unique part of Canadian life.<ref name=Valerie />\n\n== Beginnings ==\n\nDuring the [[First Indochina War]] between France and the Indo-Chinese nationalist and communist parties, Canada remained militarily uninvolved but provided modest diplomatic and economic support to the French.  Canada was, however, part of the [[International Control Commission]] (along with Poland and India) that oversaw the [[Geneva Conference (1954)|1954 Geneva Agreements]] that divided Vietnam, provided for French withdrawal and would have instituted elections for reunification by 1956.  Behind the scenes, Canadian diplomats tried to discourage both France and the United States from escalating the conflict in a part of the world Canadians had decided was not strategically vital.{{Citation needed|date=February 2007}}\n\nCanada laid out six prerequisites to joining a war effort or Asian alliance like [[Southeast Asia Treaty Organization|SEATO]]:\n# It had to involve cultural and trade ties in addition to a military alliance.\n# It had to demonstrably meet the will of the people in the countries involved.\n# Other free Asian states had to support it directly or in principle.\n# France had to refer the conflict to United Nations.\n# Any multilateral action must conform to the [[United Nations Charter|UN charter]].\n# Any action had to be divorced from all elements of [[colonialism]].{{Citation needed|date=February 2007}}\n\nThese criteria effectively guaranteed Canada would not participate in the Vietnam War.\n\n== Canadian involvement in the war ==\n[[File:Lorne RodenBush -- Canadian observer during the War in Vietnam.jpg|thumb |right |alt=Canadian military officer standing in uniform beside Canadian flag |Colonel Lorne RodenBush was Canada's representative to the [[International Control Commission]] in Vietnam from 1967\u2013 \n68.<ref>Bardua, Rob (April 9, 2008).  \"[http://www.nationalmuseum.af.mil/news/story.asp?id=123093763 Canadian Colonel to Speak About His Experiences in Hanoi During the Vietnam War] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141103082754/http://www.nationalmuseum.af.mil/news/story.asp?id=123093763 |date=November 3, 2014 }}\".  National Museum of the US Air Force website.  Retrieved December 11, 2012.</ref>]]\nAt the start of the Vietnam War, Canada was a member of the [[International Control Commission]] (ICC) overseeing the implementation of the Geneva Agreements, and thus attempted to maintain an air of neutrality.  However, the Canadian negotiators were strongly on the side of the Americans. One representative ([[J. Blair Seaborn]], younger brother of [[Robert Seaborn]]) was even involved in secretly exchanging messages between the U.S. and North Vietnam on behalf of the Americans, with the approval of the Canadian government. Canada also sent foreign aid to South Vietnam, which, while humanitarian, was directed by the Americans.<ref name=\"Vietnam War\">\"[http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/en/article/vietnam-war/ \"Vietnam War\"]. ''The Canadian Encyclopedia.''</ref>\nCanada tried to mediate between the warring countries, aiming for a conclusion that could allow the U.S. to leave the conflict honorably, but also reportedly publicly (if mildly) criticized American war methods.{{Citation needed|date=February 2007}} Text of a speech which Canadian Prime Minister Lester Pearson gave at Temple University in Philadelphia in 1965 has debunked this widespread rumor, with Pearson even stating \"The government and great majority of people of my country have supported wholeheartedly the US peacekeeping and peacemaking policies in Vietnam.\"<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=J3_FBQAAQBAJ&pg=PT86&lpg=PT86&dq=The+government+and+great+majority+of+people+of+my+country+have+supported+wholeheartedly+the+US+peacekeeping+and+peacemaking+policies+in+Vietnam+lester+pearson&source=bl&ots=8oBPP0fHOk&sig=ACfU3U1gHp2va1K5ZBZUJKVRizvOtTAVtA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjj04WoloXlAhVFmK0KHZITBHsQ6AEwAXoECAgQAQ#v=onepage&q=The%20government%20and%20great%20majority%20of%20people%20of%20my%20country%20have%20supported%20wholeheartedly%20the%20US%20peacekeeping%20and%20peacemaking%20policies%20in%20Vietnam%20lester%20pearson&f=false|title=The Globalization of NATO: Intervention, Security and Identity|first=Veronica M.|last=Kitchen|accessdate=5 October 2019}}</ref><ref>https://yvesengler.com/2016/03/15/why-does-mainstream-keep-repeating-lies-about-lester-pearson/</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=9g4Xd12rIGYC&pg=PT88&lpg=PT88&dq=Linda+McQuaig++contributed+to+ending+the+U.S.+war+effort+in+Vietnam.&source=bl&ots=isGKlO1Yei&sig=Ju_jcwsBsMODmOLHHfz4946wJ8s&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiC_5i2sMLLAhVHlYMKHX4eAbEQ6AEIGzAA#v=onepage&q=Linda%20McQuaig%20%20contributed%20to%20ending%20the%20U.S.%20war%20effort%20in%20Vietnam.&f=false|title=Holding the Bully's Coat: Canada and the U.S. Empire|first=Linda|last=McQuaig|accessdate=5 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, Canadian industry exported military supplies and raw materials useful in their manufacture, including ammunition, [[napalm]] and [[Agent Orange]],<ref name=\"supplying\">[http://archives.cbc.ca/IDC-1-71-1413-9128/conflict_war/vietnam/clip7 Supplying the war machine] \u2013 [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]] Archives</ref> to the United States, as trade between the two countries carried on unhindered.\n\n\"500 firms sold $2.5 billion of war materials (ammunition, napalm, aircraft engines and explosives) to the Pentagon. Another $10 billion in food, beverages, berets and boots for the troops was exported to the U.S., as well as nickel, copper, lead, oil, brass for shell casings, wiring, plate armour and military transport. In Canada unemployment fell to record low levels of 3.9%\".<ref name=\"Vietnam War\"/>\n\nAlthough these exports were sales by Canadian companies, not gifts from the Canadian government, they benefited the American war effort nonetheless. The first official response to the economic support being given to the United States military from the government was by [[Lester B. Pearson]] on March 10, 1967 that the export of goods to their southern ally was \"necessary and logical\" due to the extreme integration of both economies, and that an embargo would also be a notice of withdrawal from North American defense arrangements.<ref>\"Thakur, Ramesh C.(1984). Peacekeeping in Vietnam: Canada, India, Poland, and the International Commission. The University of Alberta Press. p.205. {{ISBN|0-88864-037-4}}.</ref>\n\nAs the war escalated, relations between Canada and the United States deteriorated.  On April 2, 1965, Pearson gave a speech at [[Temple University]] in the United States which, in the context of firm support for U.S. policy, called for a pause in the bombing of North Vietnam. In a perhaps apocryphal story, when a furious [[President of the United States|President]] [[Lyndon B. Johnson]] met with Pearson the next day, he grabbed the much smaller Canadian by his lapels and talked angrily with him for an hour. After this incident, the two men somehow found ways to resolve their differences over the war\u2014in fact, they both had further contacts, including later twice meeting in Canada.<ref>{{cite book|last=Martin|first=Lawrence|title=The Presidents and the Prime Ministers|url=https://archive.org/details/presidentsprimem0000mart|url-access=registration}}</ref>\n\n== Assistance to the U.S. war effort ==\n\n[[File:DHC-4 Caribou Vietnam.jpg|thumb |upright=1.2 |right |alt=Large airplane descending over tarpaulin-covered area |A [[de Havilland Canada DHC-4 Caribou]] transport plane on landing approach, Vietnam War, 1971.]]\nCanada's official diplomatic position in relation to the Vietnam War was that of a non-belligerent, which imposed a ban on the export of war-related items to the combat areas.{{Citation needed|date=November 2007}} Nonetheless, Canadian industry was also a major supplier of equipment and supplies to the American forces, not sending these directly to [[South Vietnam]] but to the United States. Sold goods included relatively benign items like boots, but also aircraft, munitions, napalm and commercial [[defoliant]]s, the use of which was fiercely opposed by anti-war protesters at the time. \nIn accordance with the 1956<ref>[http://www.ccc.ca/en/canadian-exporters/~/media/9513A3BD3C1448FE8970C22641DD337C.ashx?la=en Full text] (pdf)</ref> [[Defence Production Sharing Agreement]], Canadian industry sold $2.47 billion in materiel to the United States between 1965 and 1973.<ref name = \"supplying\"/> Many of the companies were owned by US parent firms, but all export sales over $100,000 US (and thus, the majority of contracts) were arranged through the [[Canadian Commercial Corporation]], a [[crown corporation]] which acted as an intermediary between the [[United States Department of Defense]] and Canadian industry.<ref name = \"supplying\"/> In some cases Canadian defence contractors were even sent to the theatre of war to carry out company work such as when [[de Havilland Canada]] sent mobile repair teams from the Downsview (Toronto) plant to carry out depot level repair on battle damaged [[de Havilland Canada DHC-4 Caribou|de Havilland Caribou]] aircraft that were owned and operated by the U.S. Army. Furthermore, the [[Department of National Defence (Canada)|Canadian]] and the [[United States Department of Defense|American Defence departments]] worked together to test chemical defoliants for use in Vietnam.<ref name = \"finkelconrad\">This collaboration was only revealed to the public in 1981. \"History of the Canadian Peoples, 1867\u2013Present,\" Alvin Finkel & Margaret Conrad, 1998</ref> Canada also allowed their [[NATO]] ally to use Canadian facilities and bases for training exercises and weapons testing as per existing treaties.\n\nBetween January 28, 1973 and July 31, 1973, Canada provided 240 peacekeeping troops to ''Operation Gallant'', the peace keeping operation associated with the [[International Commission of Control and Supervision]] (ICCS) Vietnam, along with [[Hungary]], Indonesia, and [[Poland]].<ref name=\"moise\">[http://www.clemson.edu/caah/history/facultypages/EdMoise/icc.html Vietnam War Bibliography: The International Commissions: ICC (ICSC) and ICCS] Edwin Moise.</ref>  Their role was to monitor the cease-fire in South Vietnam per the [[Paris Peace Accords]].<ref>[http://www.vac-acc.gc.ca/remembers/sub.cfm?source=collections/cmdp/mainmenu/group06/icmvn Control and Supervision Vietnam 1973 \u2013 ICCS], Veterans Affairs Canada, March 26, 2001</ref> After Canada's departure from the Commission, it was replaced by [[Iran]].\n\n== Canadians in the U.S. military ==\n\n[[File:WindsorCanadianDeadVietnamwar.jpg|thumb |upright=1.2 |right |alt=Large brown house behind Canadian and American flags |The [[Canadian Vietnam Veterans Memorial]] in Windsor, Ontario, commemorates Canadians who died fighting alongside American forces in Vietnam.]]\n\n[[File:Peter C Lemon.jpg|thumb|right|alt=Head shot of a confident-looking young man in an Army uniform.|Toronto-born [[Peter C. Lemon]] served with distinction in the U.S. Army in Vietnam.]]\n\nIn a counter-current to the movement of American draft evaders and deserters to Canada, about 30,000 Canadians volunteered to fight in southeast Asia.<ref name=\"cbcsecretwar\">{{cite news| title =Canada's Secret War: Vietnam| publisher =CBC| url =http://archives.cbc.ca/IDD-1-71-1413/conflict_war/vietnam/| accessdate =April 7, 2007 }}</ref> Among the volunteers were fifty [[Mohawk nation|Mohawks]] from the [[Kahnawake|Kahnawake reserve]] near Montreal.<ref name=\"mohawksinvietnam\">{{cite book| last =Morrison| first =Wilbur H.| title =The Elephant and the Tiger| publisher =Hellgate Press| year =2001| page =597| isbn = 1-55571-612-1 }}</ref> One hundred ten Canadians died in Vietnam, and seven remain listed as [[Missing in Action|missing in action]]. U.S. Army [[Sergeant]]   [[Peter C. Lemon]], an American [[immigrant]] from Canada, was awarded the U.S. [[Medal of Honor]] for his valour in the conflict. (This cross-border enlistment was not unprecedented:  Both the [[World War I|First]] and the [[Second World War]] saw thousands of Americans join the Canadian Armed Forces before the U.S officially declared war on Germany)<ref name=\"Malley-Morrison2009\">{{cite book|author=Kathleen Malley-Morrison|title=State Violence and the Right to Peace: Western Europe and North America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hV-y4BNWTt0C&pg=PA167|accessdate=June 12, 2011|date=October 30, 2009|publisher=[[ABC-CLIO]]|isbn=978-0-275-99651-2|pages=167\u2013}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Windsor, Ontario]], there is a privately funded monument to the Canadians killed in the Vietnam War.<ref name=\"ontmonument\">{{cite web| title =Canadian Vietnam Memorial \u2013 \"The North Wall\"| publisher =Edna Barney (self published)| url =http://barneykin.com/northwall/| accessdate =April 7, 2007 }}</ref> In [[Melocheville, Quebec]], there is a monument dating from October 1989 funded by the Association Qu\u00e9b\u00e9coise des V\u00e9t\u00e9rans du Vietnam.<ref name=\"qcmonument\">{{cite web| title =Canadian Vietnam Veterans Monument| publisher =Association Qu\u00e9b\u00e9coise des V\u00e9t\u00e9rans du Vietnam| url =http://www.canadianvietnamvetsquebec.com/#!our-history/c1050}}</ref>\n\n==American war resisters in Canada==\n{{Main|War resister}}\nAmerican [[draft evasion|draft evaders]] (often referred to by the disparaging term \"draft dodgers\") and military [[deserter]]s who sought refuge in Canada during the Vietnam War would ignite controversy among those seeking to immigrate to Canada, some of it provoked by the Canadian government's initial refusal to admit those who could not prove that they had been discharged from [American] military service. This changed in 1968.<ref name=\"knowles\">{{Cite journal|last1= Knowles|first1=Valerie|title=Forging Our Legacy: Canadian Citizenship and Immigration, 1900\u20131977|publisher=[[Public Works and Government Services Canada]], [[Citizenship and Immigration Canada]]|year=2000|isbn=0662289838}}</ref> On May 22, 1969, Ottawa announced that immigration officials would not and could not ask about immigration applicants' military status if they showed up at the border seeking permanent residence in Canada.<ref name=\"cool\"/> According to Valerie Knowles, draft evaders were usually college-educated sons of the middle class who could no longer defer induction into the [[Selective Service System]]. Deserters, on the other hand, were predominantly sons of the lower-income and working classes who had been inducted into the armed services directly from high school or who had volunteered, hoping to obtain a skill and broaden their limited horizons.<ref name=\"knowles\"/>\n\nStarting in 1965, Canada became a choice haven for American draft evaders and deserters. Because they were not formally classified as refugees but were admitted as immigrants, there is no official estimate of how many draft evaders and deserters were admitted to Canada during the Vietnam War. One informed estimate puts their number between 30,000 and 40,000.<ref name=\"knowles\"/> Whether or not this estimate is accurate, the fact remains that emigration from the United States was high as long as America was involved militarily in the war and maintained compulsory military service; in 1971 and 1972 Canada received more immigrants from the United States than from any other country.<ref name=\"knowles\"/>\n\n=== Draft evaders ===\n{{main|Draft evasion}}\n[[File:Draft dodgers being counseled 1967.jpg|thumb |upright=1.2 |right |alt=Five young people sitting and talking intently |[[Mark Satin]] (left) counseling American Vietnam War evaders at the Anti-Draft Programme office in Toronto, 1967.]]\nEstimates vary greatly as to how many Americans settled in Canada for the specific reason of dodging the draft or \"evading [[conscription]],\" as opposed to desertion, or other reasons.  Canadian immigration statistics show that 20,000 to 30,000 draft-eligible American men came to Canada as immigrants during the Vietnam era. The [[BBC]] stated that \"as many as 60,000 young American men dodged the draft.\"<ref>{{cite news |first= Jeff|last=Gray |title=US deserter's Canadian campaign |date= July 6, 2004|publisher=BBC|accessdate=January 19, 2009|quote= |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/3867481.stm}}</ref>  Estimates of the total number of American citizens who moved to Canada due to their opposition to the war range from 50,000 to 125,000<ref name=\"dogers\">[http://www.cbc.ca/canada/story/2004/09/08/draft_dogers040908.html draft dodgers memorial to be built in B.C.], CBC News, 09/08/2004</ref> This exodus was \"the largest politically motivated migration from the United States since the [[United Empire Loyalist]]s moved north to oppose the [[American Revolution]].\"<ref name = \"strawberry\">\"On Strawberry Hill\" by Chris Turner in [[The Walrus]], September 2007.</ref> Major communities of war resisters formed in Montreal, the [[Slocan Valley]], British Columbia, and on [[Baldwin Village|Baldwin Street]] in [[Toronto]], Ontario.{{Citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\nThey were at first assisted by the Student Union for Peace Action, a campus-based Canadian anti-war group with connections to [[Students for a Democratic Society (1960 organization)|Students for a Democratic Society]].<ref>Clausen, Oliver (May 21, 1967).  \"Boys Without a Country\".  ''The New York Times Magazine'', p.&nbsp;25.</ref><ref>Williams, Roger N. (1971).  ''The New Exiles: War Resisters in Canada''.  Liveright Publishers, pp.&nbsp;\n61\u201364. {{ISBN|978-0-87140-533-3}}.</ref>  Canadian immigration policy at the time made it easy for immigrants from all countries to obtain legal status in Canada.<ref>Schreiber, Jan (January 1968).  \"Canada's Haven for Draft Dodgers\".  ''The Progressive'', p.&nbsp;34.</ref>  By late 1967, draft evaders were being assisted primarily by several locally based anti-draft groups (over twenty of them), such as the Vancouver Committee to Aid American War Objectors<ref>Berton, Pierre (1997).  ''1967: The Last Good Year''.  Doubleday Canada, p.&nbsp;202. {{ISBN|978-0-385-25662-9}}.</ref><ref>Williams, Roger N. (1971), cited above, pp.&nbsp;56\u201358.</ref> and the Toronto Anti-Draft Programme.<ref>Cowan, Edward (February 11, 1968).  \"Expatriate Draft Evaders Prepare Manual on How to Immigrate to Canada\".  ''The New York Times'', p. 7.</ref><ref>Hagan, John (2001).  ''Northern Passage: American Vietnam War Resisters in Canada''.  Harvard University Press, pp.&nbsp;74\u201380. {{ISBN|978-0-674-00471-9}}.</ref>  As a counselor for the Programme, [[Mark Satin]] wrote the ''Manual for Draft-Age Immigrants to Canada'' in 1968.<ref>Jones, Joseph (spring\u2013summer 2002).  \"The House of Anansi's Singular Bestseller\".  ''[[Canadian Notes & Queries]]'', issue no 61, p.&nbsp;19.</ref><ref name=Roy>[[Roy MacSkimming|MacSkimming, Roy]] (26 August 2017).  \"[https://beta.theglobeandmail.com/arts/books-and-media/book-reviews/review-mark-satins-manual-for-draft-age-immigrants-to-canada-is-just-as-timely-as-ever/article36087618  Review: Mark Satin's Manual for Draft-Age Immigrants to Canada Is Just as Timely as Ever]\". ''The Globe and Mail'' (Toronto), p.&nbsp;R12. Online dated one day earlier.  Retrieved 6 December 2017.</ref>  It sold nearly 100,000 copies overall.<ref>Adams, James (October 20, 2007).  \"[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/the-big-guys-keep-being-surprised-by-us/article696023 'The Big Guys Keep Being Surprised By Us']\". ''The Globe and Mail'' (Toronto), p.&nbsp;R6.  Retrieved December 12, 2012.</ref><ref name=Fulford>[[Robert Fulford (journalist)|Fulford, Robert]] (6 September 2017).  \"[https://nationalpost.com/entertainment/books/how-vietnam-war-draft-dodgers-became-a-lively-and-memorable-part-of-canadian-history  How Vietnam War Draft Dodgers Became a Lively and Memorable Part of Canadian History]\".  ''[[National Post]]'' (Canada), national edition, p.&nbsp;B5.  Retrieved 6 December 2017.</ref>  In 1970, Canadian singer [[Gordon Lightfoot]] recorded his song \"Sit Down Young Stranger\" to express his views on Canada's acceptance of American draft evaders.{{Citation needed|reason=Not obvious from lyrics|date=December 2017}}\n\n[[File:Hendricks-leboeuf2.jpg|thumb|right|alt=Joyful-looking male couple holding a wedding bouquet|Quebec gay rights advocate [[Michael Hendricks and Ren\u00e9 Leboeuf|Michael Hendricks]] (right) is one American war resister who affected Canadian life.]]\n\nThe influx of these young men, who (as mentioned earlier) were often well educated<ref name=\"knowles\"/><ref name=\"star20090705\">{{cite news |first=Sue |last= Bailey|title=Iraq war resisters decry Tories' website editing |url= https://www.thestar.com/article/661072|work=The Toronto Star|date= July 5, 2009|accessdate=July 22, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"letthemstay\">{{cite web | title=Vietnam War Resisters, Then and Now | url=http://www.letthemstay.ca/english_index.htm | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141109133025/http://www.letthemstay.ca/english_index.htm | url-status=dead | archive-date=November 9, 2014 | accessdate=May 24, 2009 }}</ref> and politically leftist, affected Canada's academic and cultural institutions, and Canadian society at large.  These new arrivals tended to balance the \"[[brain drain]]\" that Canada had experienced.  While some draft evaders returned to the United States after a [[pardon]] was declared in 1977 during the administration of [[Jimmy Carter]], roughly half of them stayed in Canada.<ref>Hagan, John (2001), cited above, pp.&nbsp;167 and&nbsp;242.</ref>\n\nProminent draft evaders who stayed in Canada permanently, or for a significant amount of time, have included:\n* Mike Fisher \u2013 founding member of [[Heart (band)|Heart]], notable rock/pop band<ref>[http://jam.canoe.ca/Music/Pop_Encyclopedia/H/Heart.html JAM! Music] \u2013 Pop Encyclopedia</ref>\n* [[William Gibson]] \u2013 science fiction writer, winner of a [[Nebula Award]]\n* [[Jim Green (councilman)|Jim Green]] \u2013 Vancouver city councillor and mayoral candidate\n* [[Michael Hendricks and Ren\u00e9 Leboeuf|Michael Hendricks]] \u2013 gay rights advocate<ref name=\"letthemstay\"/>\n* [[Jeffry House]] \u2013 lawyer, clients include many activists\n* Bill King \u2013 musician and organizer of Toronto's [[Beaches Jazz Festival]]<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.inthesetimes.com/article/6949/sanctuary_denied/ |title=Sanctuary Denied |author= Roman Goergen|date= February 23, 2011|magazine=[[In These Times]] |accessdate=March 6, 2011}}</ref>\n* Michael Klein \u2013 activist physician, spouse of [[Bonnie Sherr Klein]], father of [[Naomi Klein]]<ref name=\"cool\"/><ref name=\"letthemstay\"/>\n* [[Keith Maillard]] \u2013 professor or creative writing, [[University of British Columbia]]\n* [[Eric Nagler]] \u2013 children's entertainer on [[The Elephant Show]]\n* Wayne Robinson \u2013 father of [[Svend Robinson]], former Member of Parliament\n* [[Jay Scott]] \u2013 film critic, ''[[The Globe and Mail]]''\n* [[Jesse Winchester]] \u2013 singer-songwriter\n* Michael Wolfson \u2013 assistant chief statistician at [[Statistics Canada]]<ref name=\"cool\">{{cite web |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/insight/article/850824--daring-to-object-iraq-war-resisters-though-often-veterans-themselves-have-been-met-with-a-cool-reception-much-different-from-the-draft-dodgers-of-the-1960s |title=Iraq war resisters meet cool reception in Canada |author=Nicholas Keung |date=August 20, 2010 |work=Toronto Star |accessdate=August 24, 2010}}</ref>\n* Harry Yates \u2013 human resources manager at the Ministry of the [[Attorney General of British Columbia]]\n\n=== Deserters ===\n{{Main|Desertion}}\n[[File:Mike Tulley Interview - October 6 2010.ogv|thumb|upright=1.2|right|Interview with Mike Tulley, an American Vietnam War deserter who emigrated to Canada.  (For interview, click on gray arrow at lower left of photo.)]]\nDistinct from draft resisters, there were also deserters from the American forces who also made their way to Canada. There was pressure from the United States and Canada to have them arrested, or at least stopped at the border.{{Citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\nThe deserters have not been pardoned and may still face ''pro forma'' arrest, as the case of Allen Abney demonstrated in March 2006.<ref name=\"thecurrent\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/thecurrent/2006/200603/20060314.html|title=CBC Radio {{!}} The Current {{!}} Whole Show Blow-by-Blow|last=Tremonti|first=Anna Maria|date=March 14, 2006|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]], Radio, The Current|accessdate=January 21, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071119190933/http://www.cbc.ca/thecurrent/2006/200603/20060314.html|archivedate=November 19, 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"Abney\">{{citenews|title=Deserter says he was treated well by U.S. military|url=http://www.cbc.ca/canada/story/2006/03/20/abney060320.html|date=March 20, 2006|accessdate=January 27, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090822210447/http://www.cbc.ca/canada/story/2006/03/20/abney060320.html|archivedate=August 22, 2009}}, CBC News</ref>  Another similar case was that of Richard Allen Shields:   He had deserted the U.S. Army in Alaska in 1972 after serving a year in Vietnam. Twenty-eight years later, on March 22, 2000, while he attempted to drive a lumber truck across the US-Canada border (in Metaline Falls, Washington) he was arrested by U.S. Customs agents and jailed at [[Fort Sill]].\nHe was discharged from the Army with an [[Other Than Honorable]] discharge in April 2000.{{Citation needed|date=December 2017}}\nOther noteworthy deserters from that era include the following:\n* [[Andy Barrie]]- former host of [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] Radio's ''[[Metro Morning]]'' in [[Toronto]]<ref name=\"cool\" /><ref name=\"letthemstay\"/> (He later received a General Discharge from the United States Army, became a [[Canadians|Canadian]] citizen, and is free to travel to the U.S.)\n* Dick Cotterill<ref name=\"letthemstay\"/>\n* Michael Shaffer: \"After six months in the Army, my application for CO status was denied and I was told that I would be going to Vietnam. I refused to draw my weapon and was ordered court-martialed. On Labour Day 1970 I was able to escape and cross into Canada ... During [[Presidency of Gerald Ford#Clemency for draft dodgers|President Ford's Clemency Program]] in 1975, I went to Fort Dix seeking the \"Undesirable Discharge\" offered to deserters who turned themselves in. The Army decided that I wasn't eligible and court-martial proceedings were resumed. With help from the ACLU, I was released and two years later a Federal Court ordered the Army to discharge me Honourably as a Conscientious Objector ... I remained in Vancouver\"<ref name=\"letthemstay\"/>\n* [[Jack Todd (journalist)|Jack Todd]] \u2013 award-winning sports columnist for the ''[[Montreal Gazette]]''\n* Mike Tulley - [[Edmonton, Alberta]] area sound engineer and social activist<ref>(January 8, 2006) \"[http://www.canada.com/edmontonjournal/news/cityplus/story.html?k=76378&id=54e519a1-5289-4b95-9ce4-931ee14b8153 Soundman quietly supports his causes] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151019122906/http://www.canada.com/edmontonjournal/news/cityplus/story.html?k=76378&id=54e519a1-5289-4b95-9ce4-931ee14b8153 |date=October 19, 2015 }}\", [[Edmonton Journal]], Retrieved December 12, 2012</ref>\n\n===Missing-text controversy===\n\nIn February 2009, text on how both draft evaders and resisters of the Vietnam War were ultimately allowed to stay in Canada suddenly vanished from the website of the [[Department of Citizenship and Immigration Canada|Department of Citizenship and Immigration]] [[Government of Canada|Canada]].\"<ref name=\"star20090705\"/><ref name=\"Bailey\">{{cite news |first=Sue |last=Bailey |title=Federal website changes undermine Iraq resisters: critics |url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/canadianpress/article/ALeqM5iGSn-j73WQhIktgHT2tLCndsL_5A |publisher= [[The Canadian Press]] |date= July 5, 2009|accessdate=July 17, 2009}}</ref>\n\nOriginally, the [[Government of Canada]] website had contained the following statements:\n\n<blockquote>... Starting in 1965, Canada became a choice haven for American draft resisters and deserters, ... Although some of these transplanted Americans returned home after the Vietnam War, most of them put down roots in Canada, making up the largest, best-educated group this country had ever received.<ref name=\"star20090705\"/></blockquote>\n\nThe above statement (now gone from the website) was part of an extensive online chapter on draft resisters and deserters from the Vietnam war, which was found in the larger online document,\"Forging Our Legacy: Canadian Citizenship and Immigration, 1900\u20131977\"<ref name=\"knowles\"/> It was originally posted on the [[Government of Canada]] website in the year 2000, when the [[Liberal Party of Canada]], led by [[Jean Chr\u00e9tien]], was in power and responsible for the content of that website. But in 2009, [[28th Canadian Ministry|the Ministry]] of [[Stephen Harper]] [took] \"a much dimmer view of [[Canada and Iraq War Resisters|dozens of U.S. soldiers who've come north after refusing to serve]] in [[2003 invasion of Iraq|the invasion of Iraq]]. Some had already been [[Canada and Iraq War Resisters#Punishments given to Iraq War resisters|deported to face military jail terms ranging from about six to 15 months]].\"<ref name=\"star20090705\"/>\n\nThe removal from the [[Citizenship and Immigration Canada|Citizenship and Immigration]] website occurred in the same month that its multi-party counterpart, the  [[Standing committee (Canada)|Standing Committee]] on [[Citizenship and Immigration Canada|Citizenship and Immigration]] was debating that issue:  On February 12, 2009, that multi-party committee passed, for the second time, a [[non-binding motion]] reaffirming Parliament's earlier (June 2008) vote which recommended that the government let [[Canada and Iraq War Resisters|Iraq War resisters]] stay in Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.parl.gc.ca/HousePublications/Publication.aspx?DocId=3676589&Language=E&Mode=1&Parl=40&Ses=2 |title=Minutes of the meeting of The Standing Committee on Citizenship and Immigration, February 12, 2009 |publisher=.parl.gc.ca |accessdate=February 26, 2011}}</ref> A month and a half later, on March 30, 2009, the [[House of Commons of Canada]] again voted in a non-binding [[Motion (parliamentary procedure)|motion]] 129 to 125 in favour of the committee's recommendation.<ref>{{cite news |first= Alex|last= Cooper|title= Federal court to hear American war resister's appeal|url= https://www.thestar.com/article/622278|work=Toronto Star |date= April 21, 2009|accessdate=April 23, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.parl.gc.ca/HousePublications/Publication.aspx?Language=E&Mode=1&Parl=40&Ses=2&DocId=3781662#OOB-2683958 |title=40th PARLIAMENT, 2nd SESSION, EDITED HANSARD \u2022 NUMBER 036, CONTENTS, Monday, March 30, 2009 |publisher=.parl.gc.ca |accessdate=February 26, 2011}}</ref>\n\n== After the war ==\n\n[[File:35 Vietnamese boat people 2.JPEG|thumb|right|alt=Refugees crowded together on a boat|After the war, Canada admitted many [[Vietnamese boat people]] as immigrants.]]\n\nThe Vietnam War continued to resonate in Canada long after the war was over.\n\n=== Vietnamese boat people ===\n{{main|Vietnamese Canadians}}\n\nAfter the [[Fall of Saigon|fall of South Vietnam]] in April 1975, hundreds of thousands of refugees, called [[Vietnamese boat people|boat people]], fled Vietnam and adjacent nations.  According to Canadian immigration historian Valerie Knowles, from 1979 to 1980 Canada admitted an estimated 60,000 of these refugees, \"most of whom had endured several days in small, leaky boats, prey to vicious pirate attacks, before ending up in squalid camps\".<ref name=Valerie>Knowles, Valerie (2016).   ''Strangers at Our Gates: Canadian Immigration and Immigration Policy, 1540-2015''.  Toronto: Dundurn Press, 4th ed., p.&nbsp;216 (\"Boat People\" section).  {{ISBN|978-1-4597-3285-8}}.</ref>  Knowles says it was the highest number of boat people accepted by any nation, including the United States, during that period.<ref name=Valerie />  The boat people constituted 25% of all newcomers admitted to Canada from 1978 to 1981.<ref name=Valerie />  This created a substantial Vietnamese community in Canada, concentrated especially in [[Montreal]], [[Vancouver]], and [[Toronto]].{{Citation needed|date=May 2007}}\n\n=== Cultural and political shifts ===\n\nThe Vietnam War was an important cultural turning point in Canada.  Coupled with [[Canadian Centennial|Canada's centenary]] in 1967 and the success of [[Expo 67]], Canada became far more independent and nationalistic.  The public, if not their representatives in parliament, became more willing to oppose the United States and to move in a different direction socially and politically.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Young|first1=Joe|title=U.S. Aggression in Vietnam & Canada's Complicity |date=1969|publisher=Canada Vietnam Newsletter|location=Toronto |pages=11\u201313 |url=http://collections.mun.ca/PDFs/radical/USAggressioninVietnamandCanadasComplicity.pdf|accessdate=October 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Agent Orange in New Brunswick ===\n\nIn 1981, a government report revealed that [[Agent Orange]], the controversial defoliant, had been tested at [[CFB Gagetown]], New Brunswick.<ref name=\"CBC-Orange\">[http://archives.cbc.ca/IDC-1-71-1413-9130/conflict_war/vietnam/clip9 CBC Archives]\u2014A 1981 news broadcast on Vietnam era \"Agent Orange\" testing in Base Gagetown, New Brunswick</ref><ref name=\"cbcagentorangepurple\">[http://www.cbc.ca/news/background/agentorange/ Agent Orange and Agent Purple]. CBC. Published 2007-08-21. Retrieved December 19, 2011.</ref>  In June 1966, the chemical was sprayed over nearly <span style=\"white-space:nowrap\">600&nbsp;acres&nbsp;(2.4&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>)</span> of forest inside the base.  There are differing opinions about the level of toxicity of the site;<ref name=\"cbcagentorangecancerrates\">[http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/story/2007/08/21/nb-agentorangereport.html No evidence to link cancer rates to Agent Orange: report]. CBC. Published 2007-08-21. Retrieved December 19, 2011.</ref> but, in 2006, the Canadian government said it planned to compensate some of those who were exposed.  As of 2011, some claims have been paid but the administration of the compensation program has been criticized.<ref name=\"dndexfoliants\">[http://www.forces.gc.ca/site/reports-rapports/defoliant/index-eng.asp The Use of Herbicides at CFB Gagetown from 1952 to Present Day] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111212011559/http://www.forces.gc.ca/site/reports-rapports/defoliant/index-eng.asp |date=December 12, 2011 }}. Department of National Defence. Retrieved December 19, 2011.</ref><ref name=\"agentorangecomp\">[http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/story/2011/12/16/bc-agentorange.html Dying woman denied Agent Orange payout]. CBC. Retrieved December 19, 2011.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Canada|War}}\n*[[Opposition to United States involvement in the Vietnam War]]\n*[[Baldwin Village]] \u2013 a neighbourhood and commercial street in Toronto that became the centre of the American exile community\n*[[Canada and Iraq War resisters]]\n*[[Canada\u2013Vietnam relations]]\n*[[Military history of Australia during the Vietnam War]]\n*[[New Zealand in the Vietnam War]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*''Building Sanctuary: The Movement to Support Vietnam War Resisters in Canada, 1965\u20131973'', by Jessica Squires.  Vancouver: University of British Columbia Press, 2013.  {{ISBN|978-0-7748-2524-5}}.\n*''[https://web.archive.org/web/20120626135503/http://www.cic.gc.ca/english/resources/publications/legacy/index.asp Forging Our Legacy: Canadian Citizenship and Immigration, 1900\u20131977]'', by Valerie Knowles.  Ottawa: Public Works and Government Services Canada, 2000. {{ISBN|978-0-662-28983-8}}.\n*''I Volunteered: Canadian Vietnam Vets Remember'', by Tracey Arial.  Winnipeg: Watson & Dwyer Publishing, 1998. {{ISBN|978-1-896239-14-9}}.\n*''In the Interests of Peace: Canada and Vietnam, 1954\u20131973'', by Douglas A. Ross. Toronto: University of Toronto Press, 1984. {{ISBN|978-0-8020-5632-0}}.\n*''Manual for Draft-Age Immigrants to Canada'', by Mark Satin.  Toronto: House of Anansi Press, \"A List\" reprint edition, 2017, orig. 1968.  New introduction by Canadian historian [[James Laxer]], new afterword by Satin (\"Bringing Draft Dodgers to Canada in the 1960s\"). {{ISBN|978-1-4870-0289-3}}.\n*''The New Exiles: American War Resisters in Canada'', by Roger Neville Williams.  New York: Liveright Publishers, 1970.  Includes transcripts of interviews with resisters.  {{ISBN|978-0-87140-533-3}}.\n*''[https://books.google.com/books?id=s0cBZvIftU0C&lpg=PP1&dq=Northern%20Passage%3A%20American%20Vietnam%20War%20Resisters%20in%20Canada&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q&f=true Northern Passage: American Vietnam War Resisters in Canada]'', by John Hagan. Cambridge: Harvard University Press, 2001. {{ISBN|978-0-674-00471-9}}.\n*''Quiet Complicity: Canadian Involvement in the Vietnam War'', by Victor Levant.  Foreword by Gwynne Dyer.  Toronto: Between the Lines Books, 1987. {{ISBN|978-0-919946-72-9}}.\n*''Snow Job: Canada, the United States, and Vietnam (1954\u20131973)'', by Charles Taylor. Toronto: House of Anansi Press, 1974. {{ISBN|978-0-88784-619-9}}.\n*''Strangers at Our Gates: Canadian Immigration and Immigration Policy, 1540-2015'', by Valerie Knowles.  Toronto: Dundurn Press, 4th ed., 2016, p.&nbsp;214 (\"Draft-Age Americans in Canada\" section).  Incorporates and updates parts of the Knowles booklet cited in this article.  {{ISBN|978-1-4597-3285-8}}.\n*''Unknown Warriors: Canadians in the Vietnam War'', by Fred Gaffen.  Toronto: Dundurn Press, 1990. {{ISBN|978-1-55002-073-1}}.\n*\"[https://web.archive.org/web/20070930043731/http://thecanadianencyclopedia.com/index.cfm?PgNm=TCE&Params=A1ARTA0008367 Vietnam War]\", by Victor Levant.  On the ''Canadian Encyclopedia'' website.  Accessed 14 December 2012.\n*''War Is Here: The Vietnam War and Canadian Literature'', by Robert McGill.   Kingston, Canada: McGill-Queen's University Press, 2017.  {{ISBN|978-0-7735-5159-6}}.\n\n==External links==\n\n===The war===\n\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110426043344/http://cvvq-aqvv.typepad.com/ Association Qu\u00e9b\u00e9coise des V\u00e9t\u00e9rans du Vietnam]\n*[http://www.cbc.ca/archives/topic/canadas-secret-war-vietnam  Canada's Secret War: Vietnam].  Digital archives, [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]].  \n*[http://www.cvva.ca  Canadian Vietnam Veterans Association]\n*[http://www.canadiansinvietnam.com  Canadian Vietnam Veterans Memorial Association]\n*[http://www.glanmore.org/cdncas/memorialair.html North Wall, Canadian Vietnam Veterans Memorial]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20160912133447/http://www.vvic.org/ Vietnam Veterans in Canada].   Advocacy group.\n*[http://www.vwam.com/vets/allies/canadians.html Vietnam Veterans With a Mission].  Information and pictures.\n*[http://edmoise.sites.clemson.edu/internat.html#canada  Vietnam War Bibliography: Canada].  Compiled by scholar Edwin L. Morse.\n*[https://www.cbc.ca/radio/rewind/the-vietnam-war-canada-s-role-part-one-1.3038110  The Vietnam War: Canada's Role, Part One].  Transcript of a [[CBC Radio]] broadcast.\n\n===War immigrants===\n\n* [https://discoverarchives.library.utoronto.ca/index.php/jack-pocock-memorial-collection Jack Pocock Memorial Collection], in the [https://onesearch.library.utoronto.ca/discover-archives Discover Archives] at the University of Toronto.  Material from the Toronto Anti-Draft Programme and similar organizations, mostly from 1969\u20131975.\n*[http://www.radicalmiddle.com/manual.htm Manual for Draft-Age Immigrants to Canada].  Narrative and excerpt.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130731092403/http://fisher.library.utoronto.ca/sites/default/files/satin629.pdf Mark Satin Papers], in the [https://onesearch.library.utoronto.ca/discover-archives Discover Archives] at the University of Toronto.  Includes material from the Toronto Anti-Draft Programme, mostly from 1967\u20131968.\n*[http://www.cbc.ca/archives/topic/seeking-sanctuary-draft-dodgers Seeking Sanctuary: Draft Dodgers].  Digital archives, [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]].\n*[http://www.radicalmiddle.com/tadp.htm Toronto Anti-Draft Programme].  Self-description from 1968.\n*[http://www